y, 1961\u20131990)<ref name= HKO >\n{{cite web\n  |url= http://www.weather.gov.hk/wxinfo/climat/world/eng/asia/china/qingdao_e.htm\n  |title= Climatological Normals of Qingdao\n  |accessdate= 2010-04-10\n  |publisher= [[Hong Kong Observatory]]\n  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20081122015526/http://www.weather.gov.hk/wxinfo/climat/world/eng/asia/china/qingdao_e.htm\n  |archive-date= 22 November 2008\n  |url-status= live\n  |df= dmy-all\n  }}</ref> and Weather Atlas (UV index)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weather-atlas.com/en/china/qingdao-climate|title=Qingdao, China - Detailed climate information and monthly weather forecast|last=d.o.o|first=Yu Media Group|website=Weather Atlas|language=en|access-date=2019-07-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709185259/https://www.weather-atlas.com/en/china/qingdao-climate|archive-date=9 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|date=August 2010\n}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n\n|type=China\n|1913<ref>Annette S. Biener: Das deutsche Pachtgebiet Tsingtau in der Provinz Schantung, 1897\u20131914. Institutioneller Wandel durch Kolonialisierung (Studien und Quellen zur Geschichte Schantungs und Tsingtaus. Bd. 6). Matzat, Bonn 2001, {{ISBN|3-924603-05-7}}.</ref>|58000\n|1953|916846\n\n|1964|1383433\n\n|1982|4227594\n\n|1990|6663989\n\n|2000|7494194\n\n|2010|8715100\n\n|footnote = Population size may be affected by changes on administrative divisions.\n\n|}}\n\nBy the end of 2006, Qingdao was estimated to be the home of about 8 million inhabitants, of which around 3 million reside in the Qingdao urban area. Another estimated 5 million live in other cities under Qingdao's jurisdiction. The annual birth rate is calculated around 76,507, with a [[birth rate]] of 10.15 per year per thousand, and a [[death rate]] of 6.32, both calculated on an annual basis. Living standards are among the highest of leading Chinese cities due to the strong export economy and relatively high family wages.\n\nQingdao is home to 38 [[Chinese nationalities|Chinese ethnic minorities]], which account for 0.14% of the city's total population.\n\nThere is a large Korean community in Qingdao. By 2009, there were approximately 100,000 Koreans working, studying and living in Qingdao, which makes Qingdao the second in terms of Korean population in China, following Beijing which has about 200,000 Koreans.<ref>\n{{cite news\n  |url= http://www.chinanews.com.cn/sh/news/2009/10-08/1899449.shtml\n  |script-title= zh:\u97e9\u56fd\u65c5\u5ba2\u4f4d\u5c45\u5317\u4eac\u5165\u5883\u5916\u56fd\u4eba\u4e4b\u9996\n  |date= 2009-10-08\n  |accessdate= 2009-12-01\n  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20091126170335/http://www.chinanews.com.cn/sh/news/2009/10-08/1899449.shtml\n  |archive-date= 26 November 2009\n  |url-status= live\n  |df= dmy-all\n  }}\n</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Tsingtao beer a 2015-04-07 16-56-17.JPG|left|thumb|170px|Qingdao-based [[Tsingtao beer]], China's second-largest domestic brand and its largest export brand.]]\n[[File:Views of Qingdao tower.jpg|thumb|upright|Qingdao TV Tower]]\nAn important region in Eastern China, Shandong Province has seen substantial change in its economic landscape in recent years. Much of this development has been concentrated in Qingdao.<ref name=\"KPMG\">{{Citation |year =2007 |title =Qingdao Shinan District Investment Environment Study 2007 |periodical =Report |publisher =KPMG Huazhen |url =http://www.kpmg.com.cn/redirect.asp?id=8584 |accessdate =2010-06-10 |ref = }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Qingdao has seen rapid development. With an annual growth rate of 18.9 percent in 2006, the city's GDP reached 42.3 billion, ranking first in Shandong Province and tenth out of China's top 20 cities.<ref name=\"KPMG\"/> [[Gross domestic product|GDP]] per capita comprised [[Renminbi|\u00a5]]52,895 (US$7,616) in 2008. The GDP has grown steadily at an average pace of 16% annually. In 2006, Qingdao was ranked one of six \"golden cities\" by the World Bank, out of 120 Chinese cities assessed on factors including investment climate and government effectiveness.<ref name=\"KPMG\"/> Until 2018, Qingdao's GDP reaches RMB 1200.15 billion, but a little bit negatively increased in 2019. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jiemian.com/article/4007720.html|title=2019\u5e74\u9752\u5c9bGDP\u53d1\u5e03\uff0c\u542b\u91d1\u91cf\u5230\u5e95\u591a\u5c11\uff1f{{!}}\u754c\u9762\u65b0\u95fb|website=www.jiemian.com|language=zh|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>\n\nInternationally, Qingdao is perhaps best known for its [[Tsingtao Brewery]], founded by a German-British joint venture in 1903 that produces [[Tsingtao beer]], the best-known Chinese export beer. It is also home to [[Haier]], a large [[white goods]] manufacturer, and [[Hisense]], a major electronics company. In 2002 guitar manufacturers [[Epiphone]] opened a factory in Qingdao.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gibson Qingdao Factory \u2013 All Epiphone... All The Time!|url=http://www.epiphone.com/News/Features/News/2007/Gibson-Qingdao-Factory-All-Epiphone-All-The-Time.aspx|publisher=Epiphone.com|accessdate=24 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309223924/http://www.epiphone.com/News/Features/News/2007/Gibson-Qingdao-Factory-All-Epiphone-All-The-Time.aspx|archive-date=9 March 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984 the Chinese government named a district of Qingdao a [[Special Economic Zones of the People's Republic of China|Special Economic and Technology Development Zone]] (SETDZ). Along with this district, the entire city had gone through amazing development of secondary and tertiary industries. As an important trading port in the province, Qingdao flourishes with foreign investment and international trade. [[South Korea]] and Japan in particular made extensive investment in the city. Approximately 80,000 South Korean citizens reside there.\n\nIn terms of primary industry, Qingdao has an estimated {{convert|50000|acre|km2}} of [[arable land]]. {{Cn|date=February 2020}} Qingdao has a zigzagging pattern coastline, and thus possesses an invaluable stock of fish, [[shrimp]], and other sea resources.\n\nQingdao's [[wind power]] electricity generation performs at among the highest levels in the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.compositesworld.com/articles/high-wind-in-china|title=High Wind in China|last=Gardiner|first=Ginger|website=www.compositesworld.com|access-date=2017-05-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525091629/http://www.compositesworld.com/articles/high-wind-in-china|archive-date=25 May 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Industrial zones===\n* Qingdao Special Economic and Technological Development Area\n* Qingdao Free Trade Zone\n* Qingdao High-tech Industrial Zone\n* Qingdao University Industrial Zone\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Road===\nThere are a total of {{convert|1145|km|abbr=on}} of roads in the Qingdao area, with nearly {{convert|500|km|abbr=on}} of expressways. These [[Expressways of China|National Trunk Highway System (NTHS)]] Expressways begin or pass through in Qingdao.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u56fd\u516c\u8def\u4fe1\u606f\u670d\u52a1\u7f51\uff0d\u516c\u8def\u5730\u56fe|url=http://glcx.moc.gov.cn/roadMap.jsp|publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u516c\u8def\u4fe1\u606f\u670d\u52a1\u7f51|accessdate=12 January 2013| language = zh-hans|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116200024/http://glcx.moc.gov.cn/roadMap.jsp|archivedate=16 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Expressways that begin in Qingdao are in '''Bold''':\n\n*G15 [[Shenhai Expressway]] ([[Shenyang]], [[Liaoning]]-[[Haikou]], [[Hainan]])\n*G18 [[Rongwu Expressway]] ([[Rongcheng, Shandong|Rongcheng]], Shandong-[[Wuhai]], [[Inner Mongolia]])\n*G20 [[Qingyin Expressway]] (Qingdao-[[Yinchuan]], [[Ningxia]])\nSpur Route: G2011 [[Qingxin Expressway]] (Qingdao-[[Xinhe, Shandong|Xinhe]], [[Pingdu]], Shandong)\n*G22 [[Qinglan Expressway]] (Qingdao-[[Lanzhou]], [[Gansu]])\n\nThese provincial expressways begin in or pass through Qingdao. Expressways that begin in Qingdao are in '''Bold''':\n\n*S16 [[Rongwei Expressway]] ([[Rongcheng, Shandong|Rongcheng]]-[[Weifang]])\n*S19 [[Longqing Expressway]] ([[Longkou]]-Qingdao)\n*S21 [[Xinwei Expressway]] ([[Xinhe, Shandong|Xinhe]]-[[Weifang]])\n*S24 [[Weiqing Expressway]] ([[Weihai]]-Qingdao)\n\nOther than Expressways, there are also [[China National Highways|National Highways]] that pass through or begin in Qingdao. National Highways that begin in Qingdao are in '''bold''':\n\n*[[China National Highway 204|G204]] ([[Yantai]]-[[Shanghai]])\n*[[China National Highway 206|G206]] ([[Yantai]]-[[Shantou]])\n*[[China National Highway 308|G308]] (Qingdao-[[Shijiazhuang]])\n*[[China National Highway 309|G309]] ([[Rongcheng, Shandong|Rongcheng]]-[[Lanzhou]])\n\nOn June 30, 2011, the longest bridge over water opened in Qingdao. The bridge, [[Jiaozhou Bay Bridge|Haiwan Bridge]], is {{convert|26.4|mi|1|abbr=out}} long and connects Qingdao to an offshore island, Huangdao. It would easily cross the English Channel and is almost three miles ({{convert|3|mi|abbr=out|disp=output only}}) longer than the previous record-holder, the Lake Pontchartrain Causeway in the American state of Louisiana. Haiwan Bridge is supported by more than 5,000 pillars and costs about 10 billion yuan which is about 1.5 billion dollars. The bridge was designed by the Shandong Gausu Group and the construction lasted for four years. Haiwan Bridge cut the commute between the city of Qingdao and the sprawling suburb of Huangdao by 30 minutes. At least 10,000 workers toiled in two teams around the clock to build the bridge, which was constructed from opposite ends.<ref>{{cite news|last=Eimer|first=David|title=China builds world's longest bridge|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/china/8248197/China-builds-worlds-longest-bridge.html|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=2013-03-23|location=London|date=8 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180506043910/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/china/8248197/China-builds-worlds-longest-bridge.html|archive-date=6 May 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On the same day, the [[Qingdao Jiaozhou Bay tunnel|Jiaozhou Bay Tunnel]] opened. The tunnel brought much convenience to people by supporting public buses and making transport between the two areas more convenient.\n\n===Marine===\n''Also see [[Port of Qingdao]]''\n\nQingdao (official name: Qingdao port international co. ltd.) hosts one of the world's busiest [[Port of Qingdao|seaport]]s. Cooperative relations have been established with 450 ports in 130 countries worldwide. In 2003, the annual cargo handling capacity exceeded 100 million [[ton]]s for the first time. The number of containers reached {{TEU|3.41 million|first=yes}} of cargoes.<ref>[http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/200309/21/eng20030921_124638.shtml Qingdao port sees upsurge in cargo handling capacity] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050310090903/http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/200309/21/eng20030921_124638.shtml |date=10 March 2005 }}.  People's Daily. Retrieved on 2012-11-12.</ref> By 2011, the port had become the world\u2019s sixth-busiest by Total Cargo Volume, having handled 372 million tonnes of cargo in that year. As of 2016, it was the 8th in the world in terms of TEUs (Twenty Foot Equivalent Units).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aapa-ports.org/Industry/content.cfm?ItemNumber=900#Statistics|title=Ports & World Trade|website=www.aapa-ports.org|access-date=3 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110504233752/http://www.aapa-ports.org/Industry/content.cfm?ItemNumber=900#Statistics|archive-date=4 May 2011|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Orient Ferry'' connects Qingdao with [[Shimonoseki]], Japan. There are two ferry lines connecting Qingdao with [[Republic of Korea|South Korea]]. The ''New Golden Bridge II'' operates between Qingdao and [[Incheon]], and the ''Blue Sea Ferry'' operates between Qingdao and [[Gunsan]].<ref>[http://www.seat61.com/SouthKorea.htm#Ferries%20from%20China Ferries Korea-China] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100819161509/http://www.seat61.com/SouthKorea.htm#Ferries%20from%20China |date=19 August 2010 }}. Seat61.com. Retrieved on 2012-11-12.</ref>\n\nQingdao port also includes a number of large adjacent ports including Dongjiakou.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Dongjiakou port|url=http://www.qingdao-port.com/en/gywm_1_2.jsp|website=http://www.qingdao-port.com/|publisher=Qingdao Port International Co. Ltd.|accessdate=31 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107055344/http://www.qingdao-port.com/en/gywm_1_2.jsp|archive-date=7 November 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Aviation===\nThe [[Qingdao Liuting International Airport]], {{convert|23|km|0|abbr=on}} away from city centre, is served by 13 domestic and international [[airline]]s, operating 94 routes, 12 of which are international and regional. In 2011, Qingdao Liuting International Airport was the [[List of the busiest airports in the People's Republic of China|16th busiest]] airport in the People's Republic of China with 11,716,361 passengers. A [[Qingdao Jiaodong International Airport|new civil aviation airport]] with much larger capacities will be built in Jiaozhou District.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Qingdao Airport Location Confirmed|url=http://www.wcarn.com/cache/news/29/29274.html|newspaper=World Civil Aviation Net|date=September 29, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029211011/http://www.wcarn.com/cache/news/29/29274.html|archivedate=29 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Intercity rail===\n[[File:Qingdao Railway Station 01.jpg|thumb|right|Qingdao railway station]]\nQingdao's railway development was picked up during the late 1990s. It is at the beginning of the [[Jiaoji Railway]]. Qingdao's city proper has some major railway stations, [[Qingdao Railway Station|Qingdao Station]], [[Sifang railway station|Sifang Station]],<ref>Until August 2008, travelers not from Qingdao are often confused as railway tickets to Qingdao are listed as destined for \"Sifang\". These trains are headed to Qingdao's Sifang district. The destination's name will revert to \"Qingdao\" once renovations to the larger Qingdao Railway Station is complete.</ref> Cangkou Station, Great-Seaport Station, etc.\n\nD and G series High speed trains travel on the Jiaoji High Speed Railway and reach speeds of {{convert|300|km/h|abbr=on}} on the Jinan-Qingdao Section.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u6d4e\u9752\u9ad8\u94c1\u5efa\u8bbe\u8fd1\u5e74\u65e0\u671b \u6d4e\u97521\u5c0f\u65f6\u751f\u6d3b\u5708\u5f97\u7b49\u7b49|newspaper=\u9f50\u9c81\u665a\u62a5|date=2012-10-17<!-- 08:44-->|author=\u6768\u4f20\u5fe0| language = zh-hans|quote={{lang|zh-hans|\u6d4e\u5357\u94c1\u8def\u5c40\u80f6\u6d4e\u5ba2\u4e13\u516c\u53f8\u4e00\u4f4d\u8d1f\u8d23\u4eba\u8bf4,\u80f6\u6d4e\u5ba2\u4e13\u7684\u5ba2\u8fd0\u6b63\u7ebf\u957f362.5\u516c\u91cc,\u8bbe\u8ba1\u901f\u5ea6\u6700\u9ad8250\u516c\u91cc/\u5c0f\u65f6,\u73b0\u5728\u884c\u8f66\u65f6\u901f\u4e3a200\u516c\u91cc.}}}}</ref> Services go to [[Beijing]], [[Shanghai]], [[Hefei]], [[Jinan]] and [[Tianjin]].<ref>{{cite web |script-title=zh:\u5217\u8f66\u65f6\u523b |url=http://www.qdhcz.net/listmain.asp?dip=menu01 |publisher=Qingdao railway station |accessdate=12 January 2013 | language = zh-hans |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130108071141/http://www.qdhcz.net/listmain.asp?dip=menu01 |archivedate=8 January 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>T The fastest train between Qingdao and Beijing is G206 / G205 times, 2 hours and 58 minutes needed<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.3box.cc/yunzhuifang/138.html|title=\u6c11\u751f\u8ffd\u8bbf\uff1a4\u670810\u65e5\u8d77\u9752\u5c9b\u81f3\u5317\u4eac\u4e00\u7ad9\u76f4\u8fbe \u9ad8\u94c1\u7968_555\u5f69\u7968_555\u5f69\u7968\u5a31\u4e50\u7f51_555\u5f69\u7968\u5b98\u65b9\u8ba4\u8bc1\u5e73\u53f0-\u9996\u9875|website=www.3box.cc|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>\n\nDomestic rail lines connect Qingdao with many cities in China including [[Beijing]], [[Lanzhou]], [[Chengdu]], [[Xi'an]], [[Zhengzhou]], [[Jinan]] and [[Jining, Shandong|Jining]].\n\n===Public transport==\n[[File:Qingdao Development Zone Bus K1 - Sunwin - SWB6121EV6 (Wheelchair Accessible Low-entrance) - ChangJiang Road (Middle) (16668263526).jpg|thumb|A Qingdao bus]]\nQingdao's public traffic owns 5283 large and medium-sized buses, [[Compressed natural gas|CNG]] buses {{As of|2012|lc=y}}.There are also 136 [[trolleybus]]es {{As of|2012|lc=y}}. All of the buses and trolleybuses can be accessed using the Qingdao Public Traffic [[IC Card]] ({{lang|zh-hans|{{linktext|\u9752\u5c9b|\u5361}}}}), which uses radio frequencies so the card does not have to physically touch the scanner. After that, all public transportation companies use Qingdaotong Card, the last company started to use this card is Zhenqing bus company located in The West Coast New Area of Qingdao (original Huangdao Distinct) in 2019.\n\nNon air-conditioned buses cost 1 yuan\uff08exclude tunnel bus\uff09, The volume of road passenger transport approaches 737 million  per year. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://qd.ifeng.com/a/20190527/7446762_0.shtml|title=\u9752\u5c9b\u53d1\u5e032018\u5e74\u793e\u4f1a\u8d23\u4efb\u62a5\u544a \u5168\u5e74\u5ba2\u8fd0\u603b\u91cf7.37\u4ebf\u4eba|website=qd.ifeng.com|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref> The Public Transport Brand of 'Ri-Xin Bus ({{lang|zh|{{linktext|\u65e5|\u65b0|\u5df4|\u58eb}}}})' is also known in China.\n\nThere are a number of taxi companies in Qingdao including Yiqing Company, Zhongqing Company, Jiaoyun Company and, Huaqing Company.\n\n===Subway===\n\n[[File:Rolling Stock of Qingdao Metro Line 11.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Qingdao Metro]] system has two very long suburban lines]]\n{{Main|Qingdao Metro}}\n\nAfter getting the approval from the State Council, the government announced on 18 August 2009 that Qingdao is ready to spend more than 29 billion yuan ($4.2 billion) before 2016 on its subway construction. Construction of {{convert|54.7|km|abbr=on}} of subway line 3 was completed before 2016 with a total investment of 29.2 billion yuan ($4.3 billion). Metro Line 3 is the first line in function and opened on 16 December 2015. In the long term, the city plans to build eight subway lines in downtown and some suburban districts, which account for {{convert|231.5|km|1|abbr=on}} in future.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2009-08/19/content_8588389.htm\n| title=$4.3 billion budget to boost Qingdao subway construction\n| date=2008-08-19\n| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822160023/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2009-08/19/content_8588389.htm\n| archive-date=22 August 2009\n| url-status=live\n| df=dmy-all\n}}\n</ref> As of end of May 2018, the system has an operating length of {{convert|170|km|abbr=on}}, lines in operation including [[Line 2 (Qingdao Metro)|Line 2]], [[Line 3 (Qingdao Metro)|Line 3]], [[Line 11 (Qingdao Metro)|Line 11]], and [[Line 13 (Qingdao Metro)|Line 13]].\n\n===Tramway===\n\n[[File:Qingdao_Tram,_Line_Chengyang.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Qingdao Tram]] system is operating in Chengyang District]]\n{{Main|Qingdao Tram}}\n\nQingdao Tram, her official name is: Modern tram demonstration line of Chengyang District, Qingdao, is a tram system operating in Chengyang District, Qingdao, China. It opened in 2016. The Qingdao Public Transport Group Rail Bus Co., Ltd. is responsible for operation and management. The system is only composed of 1 bus line.\n\n==Military==\nQingdao is headquarters of the [[North Sea Fleet]] of the [[People's Liberation Army Navy]].\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Architecture===\n[[File:Views of Qingdao.jpg|thumb|right|Qingdao retains many buildings with a German architectural style]]\nThere are a large number of German-style buildings in Qingdao city centre, remarkable considering the German leased-territory period only lasted 16 years (1898\u20131914). The unique combination of German and Chinese architecture in the city centre, combined with German demographic roots and a large Korean expatriate population, gives Qingdao a distinct atmosphere. An old saying described Qingdao as a city of \"red tiles green trees, blue sky and blue sea.\" This saying indeed gives a picture of bird view of Qingdao. A larger number of areas in former foreign styles are well preserved. Although the new city area is under large-scale reconstruction, the old city area (especially the western part of [[Shinan District]]) still retains many traditional buildings.\n[[File:St_Michaels_Cathedral_West_Front.png|thumb|upright|[[St. Michael's Cathedral, Qingdao|St. Michael's Cathedral]]]]\n[[File:Qingdao skyscrapers.jpg|thumb|upright|Skyscrapers in Qingdao]]\n\n===Notable people===\n*[[James R. Lilley]], US ambassador to Taiwan, South Korea and China\n*[[Ma Jian (writer)|Ma Jian]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9a6c\u5efa}})\n*[[Xiao Hong]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u8427\u7ea2}})\n*[[Xiao Jun]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u8427\u519b}})\n*[[Duanmu Hongliang]] ({{lang|zh|\u7aef\u6728\u857b\u826f}})\n*[[Erin Pizzey]], (was born in Qingdao)\n*[[Li Zhaoxing]] ({{lang|zh|\u674e\u8087\u661f}})\n*[[Zhang Ruimin]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5f20\u745e\u654f}})\n*[[Victoria Song]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5b8b\u831c}}, f(x))\n*[[Huang Zitao]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9ec4\u5b50\u97ec}}, musician,actor)\n*[[Huang Bo]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9ec4\u6e24}})\n*[[Zhang Jike]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5f20\u7ee7\u79d1}})\n*[[Gao Fenghan]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9ad8\u51e4\u7ff0}})\n*[[Toshiro Mifune]] (was born in Qingdao)\n*[[Li Cunxin (dancer)|Li Cunxin]] ({{lang|zh|\u674e\u5b58\u4fe1}})\n*[[Huang Xiaoming]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9ec4\u6653\u660e}})\n*[[Chen Hao (actress)|Chen Hao]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9648\u597d}})\n*[[Xia Yu (actor)|Xia Yu]] ({{lang|zh|\u590f\u96e8}})\n*[[Fan Bingbing]] ({{lang|zh|\u8303\u51b0\u51b0}},was born in Qingdao)\n*[[Bai Baihe]] ({{lang|zh|\u767d\u767e\u5408}})\n*[[Hao Haidong]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u90dd\u6d77\u4e1c}})\n*[[Wang Dong (footballer, born 1981)|Wang Dong]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u738b\u680b}}, Chinese Footballer)\n*[[Zhang Juanjuan]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5f20\u5a1f\u5a1f}},archer)\n*[[Malcolm H. Wiener]], (was born in Qingdao)\n*[[Ni Ping]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u502a\u840d}})\n*[[Tang Guoqiang]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5510\u56fd\u5f3a}})\n\n===Movies shot in Qingdao===\n* [[A Better Tomorrow 2018]] ({{lang|zh|\u82f1\u96c4\u672c\u8272}}2018\uff092016\n* [[The Great Wall (film)|The Great Wall]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u957f\u57ce}}) 2016\n* Underdog Fight ({{lang|zh-hans|\u786c\u6c49}}) 2008\n* Underdog Fight II ({{lang|zh-hans|\u786c\u6c49 II}}) 2013\n* [[Ocean Heaven]] ({{lang|zh|\u6d77\u6d0b\u5929\u5802}}) 2010\n* Beauty Remains ({{lang|zh-hans|\u7f8e\u4eba\u4f9d\u65e7}}) 2005\n\n===Language===\nDuring the city's leased-territory days, [[German language|German]] was the official language and rigorously taught and promoted. Since the demise of Germany's colonial empire during World War I, the German language is all but gone, leaving little impact on the local languages. A local accent known as [[Qingdao dialect]] ({{zh|c=\u9752\u5c9b\u8bdd|p=Q\u012bngd\u01ceo hu\u00e0}}) distinguishes the residents of the city from those of the surrounding [[Shandong]] province. Due to the efforts by the city government to promote standard [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]], most educated people can speak standard Mandarin in addition to their native dialect. With reform policies and English teaching, some young citizens have been taught English and many can converse with English-speaking foreigners. Business and traffic signs in English are becoming more and more common.\n\n===Cuisine===\nSeafood is a typical delicacy of the coastal city, divided into two categories: \"Great Seafood\" including [[sea cucumber (food)|sea cucumber]]s, [[abalone]]s, [[shark]]'s fin, [[prawn]]s, crabs, [[conch]], and some big fish, and \"Little Seafood\" comprising [[squid]], [[shrimp]]s, [[octopus]], [[oyster]]s, razor clams, [[clam]]s, [[Littorina|periwinkle]]s, [[yellow croaker]]s, etc.\n\nThe distinctive cuisine of the area is [[Shandong cuisine|Lu Cai]], the [[Shandong]] regional style.\n\n===Festivals===\nNotable festivals include:\n*[[Qingdao International Horticultural Exposition 2014]] is the biggest international fair that has been held in the history of the city.\n*[[Qingdao International Beer Festival]] (\u9752\u5c9b\u56fd\u9645\u5564\u9152\u8282) in August/September, held annually since 1991.\n\n==Media==\nQingdao previously had a large German community and a German garrison, so three German newspapers operated in Qingdao.<ref name=Walravens90>Walravens, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=0F6U82kZXjsC&pg=PA90&dq=%22Its+contents+covered+politics+and+economy+but+there+were%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=VYSQUN7PKIji8gSkhYGQAQ&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Its%20contents%20covered%20politics%20and%20economy%20but%20there%20were%22&f=false 90] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160102035918/https://books.google.com/books?id=0F6U82kZXjsC&pg=PA90&dq=%22Its+contents+covered+politics+and+economy+but+there+were%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=VYSQUN7PKIji8gSkhYGQAQ&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Its%20contents%20covered%20politics%20and%20economy%20but%20there%20were%22&f=false |date=2 January 2016 }}.</ref> German papers included ''[[Deutsch-Asiatische Warte]]'' ({{zh|t=\u6cf0\u6771\u53e4\u4eca\u9451|s=\u6cf0\u4e1c\u53e4\u4eca\u9274|p=T\u00e0id\u014dng G\u01d4j\u012bn Ji\u00e0n}};<ref name=Walravens91>Walravens, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=0F6U82kZXjsC&pg=PA91&dq=%22Hankou+also+had+a+German+paper%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=9rCQUKP8EpHa8wTm-YCYBA&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Hankou%20also%20had%20a%20German%20paper%22&f=false 91] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160102035918/https://books.google.com/books?id=0F6U82kZXjsC&pg=PA91&dq=%22Hankou+also+had+a+German+paper%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=9rCQUKP8EpHa8wTm-YCYBA&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Hankou%20also%20had%20a%20German%20paper%22&f=false |date=2 January 2016 }}.</ref> weekly newspaper published until 1906, included ''Die Welt des Ostens, Altes und Neues aus Asiens drei Kaiserreichen'', a cultural supplement),<ref name=Walravens90/> the ''[[Tsingtauer Neueste Nachrichten]]'' and the ''[[Kiautschou Post]]'' (a daily paper published from 1908 to 1912, referring to the [[Kiautschou Bay concession|Kiautschou (Jiaozhou) Bay concession]]). German publishing in Qingdao ended after [[World War I]] and the beginning of the Japanese administration.<ref name=Walravens91/>\n\nA 1912 publication of the [[United States Department of Commerce]], [[Bureau of Foreign and Domestic Commerce]] said that the ''[[Tageblatt f\u00fcr Nordchina]]'' of [[Tianjin]] was read in Qingdao, and that major newspapers from [[Shanghai]] were also read in Qingdao.<ref>[[United States Bureau of Foreign and Domestic Commerce]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=nsANAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA188&dq=%22Tsingtauer+Neueste+Nachrichten%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=i16UUMScH4uC8ASKooGQDQ&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=%22Tsingtauer%20Neueste%20Nachrichten%22&f=false p. 188] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160102035918/https://books.google.com/books?id=nsANAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA188&dq=%22Tsingtauer+Neueste+Nachrichten%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=i16UUMScH4uC8ASKooGQDQ&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=%22Tsingtauer%20Neueste%20Nachrichten%22&f=false |date=2 January 2016 }}. \"Tageblatt f\u00fcr Nord China, a German paper published in Tientsin, and the leading papers published in Shanghai are also largely read in Tsingtau.\"</ref>\n\n==Tourism==\nQingdao attracts many tourists due to its seaside setting and temperate weather. Parks, beaches, sculptures and unique German and modern architecture line the shore.  The central tourist information, the Qingdao Information Centre for International Visitors, is located on Middle Hong Kong Road (\u9999\u6e2f\u4e2d\u8def).\n\nQingdao's major attractions include:\n\n===Western Shinan district===\n*[[Zhan Qiao|Zhan Qiao (Pier, \u6808\u6865)]]\n*Little Qingdao Isle (\u5c0f\u9752\u5c9b)\n*Tian Hou Temple (\u5929\u540e\u5bab), Qingdao Folk Museum\n*[[Ba Da Guan|Ba Da Guan (Eight Great Passes, \u516b\u5927\u5173)]], the older area of town with some surviving German and Japanese architecture.\n*[[Lu Xun Park (Qingdao)|Lu Xun Park]], named after [[Lu Xun]] (\u9c81\u8fc5), modern Chinese writer and critic, who lived and taught in the 1930s.\n*Zhongshan Park, named after the style name 'Zhongshan' of [[Sun Yat-sen]] (\u5b59\u6587\uff0c\u5b57\u4e2d\u5c71), a famous modern Chinese politician.\n*[[Xiao Yu Shan|Xiao Yu Shan (Little Fish Hill, \u5c0f\u9c7c\u5c71)]]\n*The twin-spired [[St. Michael's Cathedral, Qingdao|St. Michael's Cathedral]] (''Kathedrale St. Michael'') (\u5929\u4e3b\u6559\u5802), one piece of the famous [[Neo-romanesque]] architecture in Qingdao, designed by German architect Alfred Fr\u00e4bel, completed in 1934.\n*[[Qingdao Aquarium]] (\u9752\u5c9b\u6c34\u65cf\u9986)\n*[[Jiaozhou Governor's Hall]] (\u63d0\u7763\u5e9c), office building of former German governors (''Gouverneurspalast'') and former municipal government\n*[[Xinhao Hill]] (\u4fe1\u53f7\u5c71)\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=Photographs of Historic Euro-Asian Area\n|width=200\n|height=200\n|lines=2\n|align=center\n|File:\u9752\u5c9b\u516b\u5927\u89c2\u82b1\u77f3\u697c.jpg|Hua Shi Lou in the Eight Great Passes\n|File:\u65e7\u9752\u5c9b\u603b\u7763\u5e9c.jpg|Former site of the headquarters of the German Administration\n|File:Christian church in Qingdao.jpg|The protestant Church (''Evangelische Kirche'') (\u57fa\u7763\u6559\u5802)\n|File:Qingdao Pier.jpg|The pier on the seafront\n|File:City View Of Qingdao 1.JPG|A view of Qingdao\n}}\n\n===Eastern Shinan district===\n*[[May Fourth Square]] (''Platz des vierten Mai''), Coastal plaza with the Wind of May sculpture\n*[[Tsingtao Brewery]] (''Tsingtao-Brauerei''), founded by Germany  and the most exported beer from China.\n*[[Zhanshan Temple]] (''Dschanschan-Tempel''), Qingdao's oldest [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] temple.\n\n===Laoshan district ({{nobold|{{lang|zh-hans|\u5d02\u5c71\u533a}}}})===\n*[[Mount Lao|Lao Shan]] (Mount Lao, Lauschan, {{lang|zh-hans|\u5d02\u5c71}}), {{convert|40|km|abbr=on}} east of Qingdao, the most famous [[Taoism|Taoist]] mountain with Taoist retreat \u2013 Great Purity Palace ({{lang|zh-hans|\u592a\u6e05\u5bab}}).\n\n===Other districts of Qingdao===\n*[[Jiaozhou Governor's Hall]] (''Gouverneurspalast''), former seat of the present and previous two governments.\n\n==Education==\n\n===Post-secondary educational institutions===\n[[File:QUST Sifang Campus Main Building.JPG|thumb|Old Main Building of Qingdao University of Science and Technology]]\nQingdao is home to a large number of [[higher education]] institutions. [[Ocean University of China]], formerly called Ocean University of Qingdao, is the most important university of maritime sciences in China. In addition, the [[Qingdao University]], the [[Qingdao University of Science and Technology]] as well as the [[Qingdao Technological University]] have also been integral parts of higher education in Qingdao for decades. Shandong University Qingdao (SDUQ) established since 2016, belonging to Shandong University System. Other institutions include:\n\n* [[China University of Petroleum (Huadong)|China University of Petroleum]], completed its relocation from [[Dongying]] to Qingdao in 2012\n* [[Shandong University of Science and Technology]], main campus is based in Qingdao since 2003\n* [[Qingdao Agricultural University]], main campus is based in Qingdao since 2007\n* [[Qingdao Technical College]]\n* [[Qingdao Binhai University]], located at Huangdao.\n\n[[Shandong University]] was located in Qingdao from 1909 to 1936. A new branch campus of the university is under construction in Aoshanwei Town, [[Jimo]].\n\n===International schools===\n*[http://kisq.e-wut.co.kr/ Korean International School of Qingdao]\n* [[Malvern College Qingdao]]\n* Pegasus California School, Qingdao\n*[[International School of Qingdao]]\n*  Qingdao Amerasia International School\n*  Qingdao No.1 International School\n*  Qingdao Oxford International College\n*  Yew Chung International School of Qingdao\n*  Belt&Road Collaborative Innovation College (BRCIC)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.brcic.cn/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=4 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104171544/http://www.brcic.cn/ |archive-date=4 November 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Secondary schools===\n* [[Qingdao No. 2 High School]]\n* [[Qingdao No. 58 School]]\n* [[Qingdao No. 9 High School]]\n* [[Qingdao No. 19 High School]]\n* [[Qingdao No. 1 High School]]\n*and so on\n\n==Sports==\nQingdao has long been a hub of professional sports in The People's Republic of China.\n\n===Stadiums===\n*[[Guoxin Gymnasium]] (Qingdao city sports center)\n*[[Yizhong Sports Center]]\n*[[Qingdao Tiantai Stadium]]\n*[[Hongcheng Stadium]]\n\n===2008 Olympic Summer Games===\nAlong with Beijing's hosting of the [[2008 Summer Olympics]], Qingdao was the host city for the Olympic Sailing competitions which took place along the shoreline by the city. These events were hosted at the [[Qingdao International Sailing Centre]] and held in [[Fushan Bay]], near the city's central business district. A hotel and an international broadcasting centre were built.\n\n===Football===\n\nQingdao is recognized as one of the \"football cities\" in China, due to dozens of preeminent players it trained like [[Qu Bo (footballer)|Qu Bo]], [[Zheng Long]], [[Yu Dabao]], [[Liu Jian (footballer)|Liu Jian]] and [[Jiang Ning]] .However, due to lack of money of the sponsors of football clubs in Qingdao, its football potential has reduced.\n\n[[Qingdao Jonoon F.C.]] (previously named Qingdao Hainiu Football Club) was founded in 1993. It is one of the founding members of the second-division of Chinese professional football league. They got the championship in their first season in 1994 and were promoted to the [[Chinese Jia-A League]]. In 1995, they finished 11th (out of a total 12 teams) and were relegated from the top league. Only one year later, after finishing as runner-up in the second-division, they returned to the top league. They have been part of [[Chinese Super League]] from its inauguration in 2004. In 2013, they were relegated to the [[China League One]] and in 2016 relegated to the [[China League Two]].\n\n[[Qingdao Huanghai F.C.]]  was established on 29 January 2013. In their first season in the Chinese Football Association Division Two League, they finished the first in league and got to the [[China League One]]. Up to June 13, 2016, they had been on the first and had a great chance to get into the Super League after the season. Fans in China called them \"Chinese [[Barcelona F.C.|Barcelona]]\".\n\n===Basketball===\n[[Qingdao DoubleStar Eagles]] is a Chinese professional basketball team which plays in the North Division of the [[Chinese Basketball Association]].\n\n===Badminton===\n[[Qingdao Renzhou Badminton Club]] is a Chinese badminton club which plays in the [[China Badminton Super League]].\n\n===Arena Football===\n[[Qingdao Clipper]] is a professional [[arena football]] team which is a member of the [[China Arena Football League]](CAFL).\n\n===Motorsport===\nThe [[IndyCar Series]] signed a contract with the Qingdao city council to hold an [[IndyCar]] race in Qingdao in 2012. The race was supposed to take place on a {{convert|3.87|mi|km|abbr=on|order=flip}} street circuit<ref>{{cite web|url=http://auto-racing.speedtv.com/article/indycar-series-confirms-china-race|title=INDYCAR: Series Confirms China Race|last=IndyCar|date=10 November 2011|work=SPEED Channel|publisher=Fox Sports|accessdate=2011-11-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111113000145/http://auto-racing.speedtv.com/article/indycar-series-confirms-china-race/|archivedate=13 November 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> but it was cancelled.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/indycar-scheduled-august-race-in-china-has-been-canceled/2012/06/13/gJQAE8bZaV_story.html|title=IndyCar scheduled August race in China has been canceled|publisher=Washington Posts|accessdate=2012-06-16}}{{dead link|date=September 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n===Surfing===\nQingdao is one of the few cities in northern China where surfing is possible. The best surfing season is during the typhoon season (June\u2013October). The south oriented beaches of Qingdao are the most appropriate to receive swells. Shinan and Laoshan districts are reported to have the best wave and wind orientation.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|China}}\n*[[List of twin towns and sister cities in China]]\n*[[Shandong]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* Gottschall, Terrell D. ''By Order of the Kaiser: Otto von Diederichs and the Rise of the Imperial German Navy 1865\u20131902''. Annapolis: Naval Institute Press. 2003. {{ISBN|1-55750-309-5}}\n* Schultz-Naumann, Joachim. ''Unter Kaisers Flagge: Deutschlands Schutzgebiete im Pazifik und in China einst und heute'' [Under the Kaiser\u2019s Flag, Germany\u2019s Protectorates in the Pacific and in China then and today]. Munich: Universitas Verlag. 1985.\n* ''Miscellaneous series, Issues 7\u201311''. [[United States Department of Commerce]], [[Bureau of Foreign and Domestic Commerce]], 1912.\n* Walravens, Hartmut. \"German Influence on the Press in China\". In: ''Newspapers in International Librarianship: Papers Presented by the Newspaper Section at IFLA General Conferences''. [[Walter de Gruyter]], January 1, 2003. {{ISBN|3110962799}}, {{ISBN|9783110962796}}.\n** [https://www.webcitation.org/6BorMkdPv?url=http://ifla.queenslibrary.org/IV/ifla62/62-walh.htm Also available at] the website of the [[Queens Library]] \u2013 This version does not include the footnotes visible in the Walter de Gruyter version.\n** Also available in Walravens, Hartmut and Edmund King. ''Newspapers in international librarianship: papers presented by the newspapers section at IFLA General Conferences''. [[K.G. Saur]], 2003. {{ISBN|3598218370}}, {{ISBN|9783598218378}}.\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Qingdao}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Qingdao}}\n* [http://www.qingdao.gov.cn Qingdao Government website] {{in lang|zh}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{Shandong}}\n{{Shandong topics}}\n{{Metropolitan cities of the People's Republic of China}}\n{{SEZ}}\n{{Most populous cities in the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Former German colonies}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Qingdao| ]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in China]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns in China]]\n", "name_user": "Rocket1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e=Public transport", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qingdao"}
{"title_page": "Antisemitism in Canada", "text_new": "{{Antisemitism}}\n'''[[Antisemitism]] in [[Canada]]''' is the manisfestation of hostility, prejudice or discrimination against the [[History of the Jews in Canada|Canadian Jewish people]] or [[Judaism]] as a [[Religion|religious]], [[Ethnic group|ethnic]] or [[Race (human categorization)|racial group]].  This form of [[racism]] has affected [[Jews]] since Canada's Jewish community was established in the 18th century.<ref>Manuel Prutschi, [http://www.jcpa.org/phas/phas-prutschi-f04.htm \"Anti-Semitism in Canada\"], Fall 2004. Accessed March 29, 2008.</ref><ref>Dr. Karen Mock, [http://www1.ca.nizkor.org/hweb/people/m/mock-karen/por-01.html \"Hate Propaganda and Anti-Semitism: Canadian Realities\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080827175159/http://www2.ca.nizkor.org/hweb/people/m/mock-karen/por-01.html |date=2008-08-27 }}, April 9, 1996. Accessed March 29, 2008.</ref>  \n\n==1800s==\nOn April 11, 1807, Jewish politician [[Ezekiel Hart]] was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of Lower Canada]] over three other [[candidate]]s, obtaining 59 out of the 116 votes cast.  Hart refused to take the [[Christianity|Christian]] based oath of allegiance and the legislature dismissed him.  Hart petitioned the legislature, saying that, while he believed that he was justified in the law in taking a seat by means of the oath used by Jews in the courts, he was willing to swear the oaths used for those elected to the assembly. After some deliberation, on February 20, 1808, the assembly resolved by a vote of 35 to 5 that \"Ezekiel Hart, Esquire, professing the Jewish religion cannot take a seat, nor sit, nor vote, in this House.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Journals of the House of Assembly of Lower Canada|date=February 20, 1808|page=144}}</ref>  The events of 1807\u20131809 are known to many as ''the Hart Affair'' ([[French language|French]]: ''L'Affaire Hart'').<ref>{{cite book |last=Douville |first=Raymond |year=1939\u20131940|chapter=L'Affaire Hart: Historical Circumstances of the Legislation Giving Jews a Status of Political Equality |title=Canadian Jewish Year Book 1 |pages=149\u2013152}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 1831, a bill was introduced in the Legislative Assembly extending the same political rights to Jews as to Christians. The bill rapidly passed both the Assembly and the Council and received the royal assent June 5, 1832.<ref>[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/3957-canada#anchor2 Jewish Encyclopedia]</ref>\n\n==1930s\u20131940s==\nBetween 1930 and 1939, Canada rejected almost all Jewish [[refugees]] from [[German occupied europe|Nazi Europe]], taking in only 4,000 of the 800,000 Jews looking for refuge, as documented in the book ''[[None Is Too Many: Canada and the Jews of Europe 1933\u20131948]]'',<nowiki/> co-authored by the [[Canada|Canadian]] historians [[Irving Abella]] and [[Harold Troper]] and published in 1983.<ref name=\":0\" /> The {{MS|St. Louis}} sailed from [[Hamburg]] in May 1939, carrying 937 Jewish refugees seeking asylum from [[Nazi]] [[Religious persecution|persecution]].<ref name=\"St. Louis Story\">{{cite web |title=The Story: The Voyage \n|url=https://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/article.php?ModuleId=10005267 |work=Voyage of the St. Louis |publisher=United States Memorial Holocaust Museum |accessdate=2012-08-30 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AJ4MkoXh?url=http://www.ushmm.org/museum/exhibit/online/stlouis/story/voyage/ |archivedate=2012-08-30 |location=Washington, DC |url-status=live }}</ref> The destination was [[Cuba]], but officials in [[Havana]] cancelled Jewish passengers' visas. Jewish [[immigration]] was strictly limited in North America, so the passengers were denied entrance to Canada and the United States.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=None is Too Many: Canada and the Jews of Europe 1933\u20131948|last=Abella|first=Irving|last2=Troper|first2=Harold|publisher=|year=1983|isbn=|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"St. Louis Story\" />\n\nOutbreaks of violence against Jews and Jewish property culminated in August 1933 with the [[Christie Pits|Christie Pits riots]]; six hours of violent conflict between Jewish and [[Christians|Christian]] youth in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]. [[Swastika]]s and [[Nazi symbolism|Nazi slogans]] began to crop up on Toronto's eastern beaches, and Jewish swimmers were attacked.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/remembering-the-christie-pits-riot/article13695461/ Remembering Toronto's Christie Pits Riot] Daniel Bitonti, The Globe and Mail, Aug.9, 2013</ref><ref>[https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2013/08/10/remembering_the_christie_pits_riot_dimanno.html Remembering the Christie Pits riot] Rosie DiManno, Toronto Star, Aug.10, 2013</ref>\n\nIn 1934, [[Adrien Arcand]] started a [[National Unity Party (Canada)|Parti national social chr\u00e9tien]] in [[Montreal]] patterned after the Nazi party. His party's actions resulted in anti-Semitic rallies, boycotts, propaganda and literature, and the inception of several other Nazi-like organizations throughout Canada. Also in 1934, all interns at [[H\u00f4pital Notre-Dame]] in Montr\u00e9al walked off the job to protest the hiring of a Jewish senior intern who had graduated from the [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al]], Dr. Samuel Rabinovitch. The dispute was resolved after several days when the new intern resigned his position. The hospital administration did arrange another internship post for Dr. Rabinovitch in St. Louis, Missouri where he remained until 1940, after which he returned to Montr\u00e9al and a medical practice.<ref>[http://www.cmaj.ca/content/169/12/1329.full \"Days of shame, Montreal, 1934\"] Peter Wilton, ''[[Canadian Medical Association Journal|CMAJ]]'' December 9, 2003, vol. 169 no. 12 p. 1329</ref><ref>[http://www.cjnews.com/node/86753 \"Doctor was central figure in 1934 hospital strike\"] David Lazarus, ''[[Canadian Jewish News]]'' November 25, 2010</ref><ref>[http://imjm.ca/location/2395 \"Dr. Sam Rabinovitch and The Notre-Dame Hospital Strike \u2013 H\u00f4pital Notre-Dame\"] Museum of Jewish Montreal</ref>\n\nIn 1938, a National [[Fascism]] Convention was held in Toronto's [[Massey Hall]].<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nAnti-semitic residential segregation was also prevalent during the 1930s and 1940s, and was accomplished through [[restrictive covenant]]s. These were agreements among owners of properties to not sell or rent to members of certain races, including Jews, or were clauses registered against [[deed]]s by land developers that restricted ownership based on racial origin. At the time, restrictive covenants could be enforced by the courts.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nA 1943 [[The Gallup Organization#Gallup Poll|Gallup poll]] put Jews in third place, behind the [[Japanese people|Japanese]] and Germans, as the least desirable immigrants to Canada.<ref name=autogenerated1>Adelman, Howard and John H. Simpson, eds. Multiculturalism, Jews and Identities in Canada. Jerusalem: Magnes Press, 1996.</ref>\n\nA 1948 article on antisemitism in Canada written for ''[[Maclean's]]'' magazine by [[Pierre Berton]] illustrates this [[racism]]: Berton hired two young women to apply for the same jobs, one under the name Greenberg, and the other under the name Grimes. While Grimes received interviews for nearly every application, positions available for Grimes were \"already filled\" when Greenberg applied, or Greenberg's applications were ignored. When Berton contacted several of these companies, he was told, \"Jews did not have the right temperament\", that \"they don't know their place\" or that \"we don't employ Jews\".<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nBerton, during his research on Canadian anti-Semitism, sent two different letters to 29 summer resorts, one signed Marshall, the other signed Rosenberg. \"Marshall\" was able to book twice as many reservations as \"Rosenberg\". Some resorts did not reply to \"Rosenberg\", and some told \"Rosenberg\" they were fully booked.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n==1950\u2013present==\nAntisemitism is still a concern in contemporary Canada.<ref name=\"2010 torstar story\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/investigations/immigration/article/793643--anti-semitism-incidents-jump-five-fold-in-canada |title=Anti-semitism incidents jump five-fold in Canada |publisher=thestar.com |date=2010-04-11 |accessdate=2010-12-10}}</ref> The non-profit [[B'nai Brith Canada]] monitors incidents and issues an annual audit of these events.\n\nIn 1989, Alberta public school teacher [[James Keegstra]] was convicted under the [[Criminal Code (Canada)|Criminal Code]] for \"wilful promotion of hatred against an identifiable group\". Keegstra had taught in his classes that the [[Holocaust denial|Holocaust was a hoax]] and that Jewish people were plotting to take over the world, and would fail students who did not reproduce his beliefs in class or in examinations.<ref>[[David Bercuson]] and Douglas Wertheimer, ''A Trust Betrayed: The Keegstra Affair'', Toronto and New York: [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]], 1985</ref> Keegstra appealed his conviction, claiming that the law infringed on his freedom of expression under the [[Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms]], with the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] eventually ruling in ''[[R v Keegstra]]'' that the infringement was justified and upheld the law.\n\nOn May 18, 2010 a Jewish public servant won \"a major human rights victory\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ottawacitizen.com/life/Public+servant+claims+rights+victory+following+anti+Semitism+complaint/3075506/story.html|title=Public servant claims rights victory following anti-Semitism complaint|last=Cobb|first=Chris|date=May 27, 2010|work=Ottawa Citizen|access-date=May 27, 2010}}</ref> against the federal government after complaining that her workplace at the Ottawa headquarters of [[Passport Canada]] was poisoned by anti-Semitism. The federal adjudicator ruled<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://decisions.fpslreb-crtespf.gc.ca/fpslreb-crtespf/d/en/item/358553/index.do|title=FPSLREB Decisions: LaBranche v. Treasury Board (Department of Foreign Affairs and International Trade)|last=Pineau|first=Michele A.|date=May 18, 2010|website=Federal Public Sector Labour Relations and Employment Board|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> that some of the public servant's fellow employees discriminated against her because of adherence to Jewish Law ([[Halakha]]) - notably leaving early each Friday to observe the Jewish Sabbath ([[Shabbat]]) and taking Jewish holidays - and that her bosses did little or nothing to help her. The situation escalated from anti-Semitic bullying at her workplace to traumatizing threats when she was accused in an anonymous anti-Semitic message to her superiors to be a [[Mossad]] agent. Another message that followed two weeks later read: \"The Jew sucks your blood. Don't fall into her trap. You will make her go swiftly or we will make her go slowly and painfully.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://decisions.fpslreb-crtespf.gc.ca/fpslreb-crtespf/d/en/item/358553/index.do|title=FPSLREB Decisions: LaBranche v. Treasury Board (Department of Foreign Affairs and International Trade)|last=Pineau|first=Michele A.|date=May 18, 2010|website=Federal Public Sector Labour Relations and Employment Board|page=6 (of the downloadable pdf)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 2, 2019}}</ref>  The public servant launched first an internal grievance against her department in January 2007 alleging breaches of the [[Canadian Human Rights Act]] (CHRA) and the no discrimination clause of the collective agreement with her employer. The grievance was rejected the following October by the federal government. She subsequently took her case to adjudication to the [[Federal Public Sector Labour Relations and Employment Board|Federal Public Service Labour Relations Board]] (FPSLREB) seeking among others damages for pain and suffering, and an admission by the government that her rights were violated. She was supported by the Canadian Association of Professional Employees (CAPE)  which stated on January 18, 2011 on its website that the decision of the FPSLREB \"was a significant win on behalf of the federal government employee.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acep-cape.ca/en/news-events/general-membership-news/news-archive-2008-2012/cape-successful-in-labranche-religious-discrimination-case/|title=CAPE Successful in LaBranche Religious Discrimination Case|last=|first=|date=January 18, 2011|website=Canadian Association of Professional Employees (CAPE)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This case received some attention in national and international media (such as the National Post, LeDroit, McLeans, USA Today, Mekor Rishon, Hamodia).      \n\nOn November 2011 an antisemitic attack took place at the south Winnipeg high school when a teen approached a 15-year-old girl as they crossed paths near his locker and began talking to her. He pulled out a lighter and started flicking it near her head, saying, \"let's burn the Jew\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Turner|first=James|title=Judge agrees lighter attack at a high school not racially motivated|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/breakingnews/Judge-agrees-lighter-attack-at-a-high-school-not-racially-motivated-238505831.html|accessdate=27 April 2014|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|date=January 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn April 12, 2012, several Jewish-owned summer homes in [[Val-Morin, Quebec]] were broken into and defaced with swastikas and anti-semitic messages.\n\nAccording to the \"2013 Audit of Antisemitic Incidents\" written by the B'nai Brith Canada, there was a decrease of 5.3% in the number of antisemitic incidents during 2013. Despite that, cases of vandalism rose by 21.8% while violence increased by one incident and harassment cases dropped by 13.9%.<ref>{{cite web|title=2013 Audit of antisemitic incidents |url=http://bnaibrith.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Audit-2013-English.pdf |work=B'nai Brith |accessdate=5 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006081950/http://bnaibrith.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Audit-2013-English.pdf |archivedate=6 October 2014 }}</ref> These incidents include antisemitic graffiti, paintings of swastikas in Jewish neighborhood, firebomb attacks, antisemitic statements, etc.<ref>{{cite web|title=Antisemitic Incidents|url=http://antisemitism.org.il/list/1|work=CFCA|publisher=CFCA|accessdate=26 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211053733/http://antisemitism.org.il/list/1|archive-date=2013-12-11|url-status=dead}}</ref> Antisemitic graffiti and swastika inscriptions has been also found during 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Photo Galleries Racist, anti-Semitic graffiti found near Ottawa River|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/racist-anti-semitic-graffiti-found-near-ottawa-river-1.2615521|accessdate=27 April 2014|newspaper=CBC News|date=Apr 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Swastika was scrawled at the entrance to Kiryas Tosh|url=http://antisemitism.org.il/article/86835/swastika-was-scrawled-entrance-kiryas-tosh|work=CFCA|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, a Toronto police published the 2014 Annual Hate/Bias Crime Statistical Report. According to the report, the victim group most targeted in 2014 was the Jewish community, with occurrence of 30% of all the hate crimes in Toronto. The total number of reported incidents that occurred on antisemitic base was 52, which makes the Jewish community to the most targeted population to assaults.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lungen|first1=Paul|title=Police find Jews most targeted for hate crimes|url=http://www.cjnews.com/news/canada?q=node/137762|accessdate=30 March 2015|work=The Canadian Jewish News|date=March 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Police find Jews most targeted for hate crimes|url=http://antisemitism.org.il/article/95184/police-find-jews-most-targeted-hate-crimes|website=CFCA|publisher=Toronto Police|accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, [[B'nai B'rith]] Canada published the \"2014 Audit of Antisemitic Incidents\". Contrasted with 2014 results, there was an increase of almost 30% in antisemitic incidents. The audit showed a peak of acts during July with the onset of operation [[2014 Israel\u2013Gaza conflict|Protective Edge]] in Gaza. According to the report, most of the incidents (1013) were defined as \"harassment\", when the fewest (19) were under the category of \"violence\".  As in previous years audits, [[Ontario]] leads the number of incidents reported at 961, or 59% of the total.<ref name=\"B'nei Brith\">{{cite web|title=2014 Annual Audit Of Antisemitic Incidents|url=https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/bnaibrithcanada/pages/174/attachments/original/1433967668/2014_report_English.pdf?1433967668|publisher=B'nei Brith|accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref>  (See section on the \"New antisemitism\" in Canada below.) \n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n|+ Annual incidents figures by category 2012\u20132014 <ref name=\"B'nei Brith\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | 2012\n! scope=\"col\" | 2013\n! scope=\"col\" | 2014\n<!-- ! scope=\"col\" | 2015 -->\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1. Vandalism\n| 319 || 388|| 238  \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2. Violence\n| 13 || 14 || 19 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3. Harassment\n| 1013 || 872 || 1370 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Total\n| 1345 ||  1274 || 1627 \n|}\nAccording to a phone survey of 510 Canadians conducted by the [[Anti-Defamation League|ADL]] (Anti-Defamation League) in 2013\u20132014,  an estimated 14% (+/&minus; 4.4%) of the adult population in Canada harbor substantial antisemitic opinions.<ref>{{cite web|title=ADL global 100- Canada|url=http://global100.adl.org/#country/canada/2014|publisher=Anti-Defamation League|accessdate=14 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2016 the Toronto Police published its annual report of hate-crimes during 2015. According to it, the Jewish population is the group most targeted to hate-crimes, especially when it comes to mischief to property occurrences.<ref name=TorontoPolice>{{cite web |url=https://www.torontopolice.on.ca/publications/files/reports/2015hatecrimereport.pdf |publisher=Toronto Police Service |title=2015 Annual Hate/Bias Crime Statistical Report |year=2015}}</ref> Moreover, in occurrences involve religion, most of the victims are part of the Jewish community (in 31 out of 58 cases). The report found that the Jewish community makes up only 3.8% of the religious population in the City of Toronto but was victimized in approximately 23% of the total hate/bias crimes in 2015.<ref name=TorontoPolice />\n\nIn July 2019, a Jewish man wearing a yarmulke was assaulted by a taxi driver in Montreal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jewish man wearing kippah assaulted by taxi driver in Montreal |url=https://www.jta.org/quick-reads/jewish-man-wearing-kippah-assaulted-by-taxi-driver-in-montreal |work=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]}}</ref>\n\n== \"New antisemitism\" in Canada ==\nIn 2009, the [[Canadian Parliamentary Coalition to Combat Antisemitism]] was established by [[List of federal political parties in Canada#Political parties currently represented in the House of Commons|major federal political parties]] to investigate and combat antisemitism - particularly what is referred to as the [[new antisemitism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cpcca.ca/about.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-05-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706173716/http://www.cpcca.ca/about.htm |archivedate=2011-07-06 }}</ref> It is argued that this form of hate targets Israel, consisting of and fed by allegations of Israeli \"war crimes\" and similar claims. Anti-Israel actions that led to the formation of a Parliamentary Coalition included boycott campaigns on university campuses and in some churches, spilling over into attacks on synagogues, Jewish institutions and individuals. Activities such as \"Israel Apartheid Week\" at [[Concordia University|Concordia]] (Montreal), York University and the University of Toronto, and boycott campaigns targeting Israel (BDS) included what some considered as \"forms of antisemitism\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.macleans.ca/education/university/utoronto-and-york-students-launch-bds-campaign/|title=UToronto and York students launch BDS campaign - Macleans.ca|date=2011-03-20|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2016/03/06/york-university-accused-of-allowing-anti-semitism-to-spread|title=York University accused of allowing anti-Semitism to spread|website=Toronto Sun|access-date=2016-09-30}}</ref>\n\nOn September 9, 2002, at Concordia University a pro-[[State of Palestine|Palestinian]] group sought to prevent a [[Anti-Netanyahu riot at Concordia University|scheduled speech]] by the then former (and now current) [[Israel]]i Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]], and the event was cancelled as a result.<ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20030115/concordia030115?s_name=&no_ads= |title=Concordia U. regrets anti-Netanyahu riot |author=Canadian Press |date=January 15, 2003 |publisher=CTV.ca |accessdate=December 25, 2019 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080601103256/http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20030115/concordia030115?s_name=&no_ads= |archivedate=June 1, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nAt York University in 2009, violent pro-Palestinian activists attacked Jewish students, shouting \"Zionism equals racism!\" and \"Racists off campus!\" One witness stated that the attackers started banging the door and windows, intimidating Jewish students and screaming antisemitic slurs such as \"Die Jew\", \"Get the hell off campus\", \"Go back to Israel\", and \"F---ing Jew\".<ref name=\"Shefa\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cjnews.com/node/82752|title=Jewish students under 'siege' at York U|last=Shefa|first=Sheri|date=February 19, 2009|work=[[Canadian Jewish News]]|access-date=March 26, 2015}}</ref> The students barricaded themselves inside the Hillel offices, where protesters reportedly banged on the windows and attempted to force their way in.  Police were called to escort Jewish students through the protesters.<ref>[http://www.jewishtribune.ca/TribuneV2/index.php/200902171360/Democracy-takes-a-beating-at-York.html Democracy takes a beating at York] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706183810/http://www.jewishtribune.ca/TribuneV2/index.php/200902171360/Democracy-takes-a-beating-at-York.html |date=July 6, 2011 }} by Atara Beck, ''The Jewish Tribune'', February 17, 2009.</ref><ref>[http://network.nationalpost.com/np/blogs/fullcomment/archive/2009/02/12/an-eyewitness-account-of-this-week-s-aggressive-intimidation-of-jewish-students-at-york-university.aspx An eyewitness account of this week's aggressive intimidation of Jewish students at York University]{{dead link|date=July 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}} by Jonathan Blake Karoly, ''National Post'', February 12, 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.canada.com/news/story.html?id=1343206 Campuses awash in tension over Israel apartheid week] By Craig Offman, ''National Post'', March 3, 2009 (posted on Canada.com).</ref><ref>[http://network.nationalpost.com/np/blogs/toronto/archive/2009/03/05/york-university-sanctions-four-student-groups-for-feb-11-incident.aspx York University sanctions student groups over rally clashes]{{dead link|date=July 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}, ''National Post'', March 5, 2009</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=12hApMpQlds|title=Krisna Saravanamuttu and Jesse Zimmerman barricade Jewish students at York|last=|first=|date=June 29, 2010|website=Youtube|publisher=|accessdate=March 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 antisemitic graffiti was scrawled on a Jewish memorial in Ottawa, and attributed to a pro-Palestinian group.\n\nLeading Canadian Jewish groups such as [[Centre for Israel and Jewish Affairs|CIJA]] and [[B'nai Brith Canada]] took the lead in responding, while other organisations such as the Canadian branch of the [[New Israel Fund]] chose not to play a role. In August 2012, CIJA opposed the [[United Church of Canada]] (UCC) boycott and divestment campaign, and CIJA's CEO [[Shimon Fogel]] distinguished between criticism of Israeli policies and initiatives that single out Israel for economic coercion.<sup>[[Centre for Israel and Jewish Affairs#cite note-14|[14]]]</sup>\n\n==See also==\n* [[:Category:Jewish museums in Canada|Jewish museums in Canada]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{citation |last =  Davies|first =Alan T. |coauthor= |year = 1992|title =Antisemitism in Canada: history and interpretation\n  |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=3kLgn7dIEwIC&lpg=PP1&dq=Antisemitism%20in%20Canada&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=true|publisher= Wilfrid Laurier University Press|isbn= 0-88920-216-8 |accessdate = }}\n* [[Montreal Holocaust Museum]]. (2018). [https://museeholocauste.ca/app/uploads/2018/10/brief_history_holocaust_reference_tool.pdf A ''Brief History of the Holocaust'']. Montreal, Quebec.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ushmm.org/museum/exhibit/focus/antisemitism/voices/transcript/?content=20080605 ''Voices on Antisemitism'' Interview with Irwin Cotler] from the [http://www.ushmm.org/ United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]\n* [http://faculty.marianopolis.edu/c.belanger/quebechistory/readings/CanadaandJewishRefugeesinthe1930s.html \"Why did Canada Refuse to Admit Jewish Refugees in the 1930's?\"]\n\n{{Antisemitism topics}}\n{{North America in topic|Antisemitism in}}\n\n[[Category:Antisemitism in Canada| ]]\n[[Category:Judaism-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in Canada]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism by country|Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Antisemitism}}\n'''[[Antisemitism]] in [[Canada]]''' is the manisfestation of hostility, prejudice or discrimination against the [[History of the Jews in Canada|Canadian Jewish people]] or [[Judaism]] as a [[Religion|religious]], [[Ethnic group|ethnic]] or [[Race (human categorization)|racial group]].  This form of [[racism]] has affected [[Jews]] since Canada's Jewish community was established in the 18th century.<ref>Manuel Prutschi, [http://www.jcpa.org/phas/phas-prutschi-f04.htm \"Anti-Semitism in Canada\"], Fall 2004. Accessed March 29, 2008.</ref><ref>Dr. Karen Mock, [http://www1.ca.nizkor.org/hweb/people/m/mock-karen/por-01.html \"Hate Propaganda and Anti-Semitism: Canadian Realities\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080827175159/http://www2.ca.nizkor.org/hweb/people/m/mock-karen/por-01.html |date=2008-08-27 }}, April 9, 1996. Accessed March 29, 2008.</ref>  \n\n==1800s==\nOn April 11, 1807, Jewish politician [[Ezekiel Hart]] was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of Lower Canada]] over three other [[candidate]]s, obtaining 59 out of the 116 votes cast.  Hart refused to take the [[Christianity|Christian]] based oath of allegiance and the legislature dismissed him.  Hart petitioned the legislature, saying that, while he believed that he was justified in the law in taking a seat by means of the oath used by Jews in the courts, he was willing to swear the oaths used for those elected to the assembly. After some deliberation, on February 20, 1808, the assembly resolved by a vote of 35 to 5 that \"Ezekiel Hart, Esquire, professing the Jewish religion cannot take a seat, nor sit, nor vote, in this House.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Journals of the House of Assembly of Lower Canada|date=February 20, 1808|page=144}}</ref>  The events of 1807\u20131809 are known to many as ''the Hart Affair'' ([[French language|French]]: ''L'Affaire Hart'').<ref>{{cite book |last=Douville |first=Raymond |year=1939\u20131940|chapter=L'Affaire Hart: Historical Circumstances of the Legislation Giving Jews a Status of Political Equality |title=Canadian Jewish Year Book 1 |pages=149\u2013152}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 1831, a bill was introduced in the Legislative Assembly extending the same political rights to Jews as to Christians. The bill rapidly passed both the Assembly and the Council and received the royal assent June 5, 1832.<ref>[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/3957-canada#anchor2 Jewish Encyclopedia]</ref>\n\n==1930s\u20131940s==\nBetween 1930 and 1939, Canada rejected almost all Jewish [[refugees]] from [[German occupied europe|Nazi Europe]], taking in only 4,000 of the 800,000 Jews looking for refuge, as documented in the book ''[[None Is Too Many: Canada and the Jews of Europe 1933\u20131948]]'',<nowiki/> co-authored by the [[Canada|Canadian]] historians [[Irving Abella]] and [[Harold Troper]] and published in 1983.<ref name=\":0\" /> The {{MS|St. Louis}} sailed from [[Hamburg]] in May 1939, carrying 937 Jewish refugees seeking asylum from [[Nazi]] [[Religious persecution|persecution]].<ref name=\"St. Louis Story\">{{cite web |title=The Story: The Voyage \n|url=https://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/article.php?ModuleId=10005267 |work=Voyage of the St. Louis |publisher=United States Memorial Holocaust Museum |accessdate=2012-08-30 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AJ4MkoXh?url=http://www.ushmm.org/museum/exhibit/online/stlouis/story/voyage/ |archivedate=2012-08-30 |location=Washington, DC |url-status=live }}</ref> The destination was [[Cuba]], but officials in [[Havana]] cancelled Jewish passengers' visas. Jewish [[immigration]] was strictly limited in North America, so the passengers were denied entrance to Canada and the United States.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=None is Too Many: Canada and the Jews of Europe 1933\u20131948|last=Abella|first=Irving|last2=Troper|first2=Harold|publisher=|year=1983|isbn=|location=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"St. Louis Story\" />\n\nOutbreaks of violence against Jews and Jewish property culminated in August 1933 with the [[Christie Pits|Christie Pits riots]]; six hours of violent conflict between Jewish and [[Christians|Christian]] youth in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]. [[Swastika]]s and [[Nazi symbolism|Nazi slogans]] began to crop up on Toronto's eastern beaches, and Jewish swimmers were attacked.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/remembering-the-christie-pits-riot/article13695461/ Remembering Toronto's Christie Pits Riot] Daniel Bitonti, The Globe and Mail, Aug.9, 2013</ref><ref>[https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2013/08/10/remembering_the_christie_pits_riot_dimanno.html Remembering the Christie Pits riot] Rosie DiManno, Toronto Star, Aug.10, 2013</ref>\n\nIn 1934, [[Adrien Arcand]] started a [[National Unity Party (Canada)|Parti national social chr\u00e9tien]] in [[Montreal]] patterned after the Nazi party. His party's actions resulted in anti-Semitic rallies, boycotts, propaganda and literature, and the inception of several other Nazi-like organizations throughout Canada. Also in 1934, all interns at [[H\u00f4pital Notre-Dame]] in Montr\u00e9al walked off the job to protest the hiring of a Jewish senior intern who had graduated from the [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al]], Dr. Samuel Rabinovitch. The dispute was resolved after several days when the new intern resigned his position. The hospital administration did arrange another internship post for Dr. Rabinovitch in St. Louis, Missouri where he remained until 1940, after which he returned to Montr\u00e9al and a medical practice.<ref>[http://www.cmaj.ca/content/169/12/1329.full \"Days of shame, Montreal, 1934\"] Peter Wilton, ''[[Canadian Medical Association Journal|CMAJ]]'' December 9, 2003, vol. 169 no. 12 p. 1329</ref><ref>[http://www.cjnews.com/node/86753 \"Doctor was central figure in 1934 hospital strike\"] David Lazarus, ''[[Canadian Jewish News]]'' November 25, 2010</ref><ref>[http://imjm.ca/location/2395 \"Dr. Sam Rabinovitch and The Notre-Dame Hospital Strike \u2013 H\u00f4pital Notre-Dame\"] Museum of Jewish Montreal</ref>\n\nIn 1938, a National [[Fascism]] Convention was held in Toronto's [[Massey Hall]].<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nAnti-semitic residential segregation was also prevalent during the 1930s and 1940s, and was accomplished through [[restrictive covenant]]s. These were agreements among owners of properties to not sell or rent to members of certain races, including Jews, or were clauses registered against [[deed]]s by land developers that restricted ownership based on racial origin. At the time, restrictive covenants could be enforced by the courts.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nA 1943 [[The Gallup Organization#Gallup Poll|Gallup poll]] put Jews in third place, behind the [[Japanese people|Japanese]] and Germans, as the least desirable immigrants to Canada.<ref name=autogenerated1>Adelman, Howard and John H. Simpson, eds. Multiculturalism, Jews and Identities in Canada. Jerusalem: Magnes Press, 1996.</ref>\n\nA 1948 article on antisemitism in Canada written for ''[[Maclean's|MacLean's]]'' magazine by [[Pierre Berton]] illustrates this [[racism]]: Berton hired two young women to apply for the same jobs, one under the name Greenberg, and the other under the name Grimes. While Grimes received interviews for nearly every application, positions available for Grimes were \"already filled\" when Greenberg applied, or Greenberg's applications were ignored. When Berton contacted several of these companies, he was told, \"Jews did not have the right temperament\", that \"they don't know their place\" or that \"we don't employ Jews\".<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nBerton, during his research on Canadian anti-Semitism, sent two different letters to 29 summer resorts, one signed Marshall, the other signed Rosenberg. \"Marshall\" was able to book twice as many reservations as \"Rosenberg\". Some resorts did not reply to \"Rosenberg\", and some told \"Rosenberg\" they were fully booked.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n==1950\u2013present==\nAntisemitism is still a concern in contemporary Canada.<ref name=\"2010 torstar story\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/investigations/immigration/article/793643--anti-semitism-incidents-jump-five-fold-in-canada |title=Anti-semitism incidents jump five-fold in Canada |publisher=thestar.com |date=2010-04-11 |accessdate=2010-12-10}}</ref> The non-profit [[B'nai Brith Canada]] monitors incidents and issues an annual audit of these events.\n\nIn 1989, Alberta public school teacher [[James Keegstra]] was convicted under the [[Criminal Code (Canada)|Criminal Code]] for \"wilful promotion of hatred against an identifiable group\". Keegstra had taught in his classes that the [[Holocaust denial|Holocaust was a hoax]] and that Jewish people were plotting to take over the world, and would fail students who did not reproduce his beliefs in class or in examinations.<ref>[[David Bercuson]] and Douglas Wertheimer, ''A Trust Betrayed: The Keegstra Affair'', Toronto and New York: [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]], 1985</ref> Keegstra appealed his conviction, claiming that the law infringed on his freedom of expression under the [[Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms]], with the [[Supreme Court of Canada]] eventually ruling in ''[[R v Keegstra]]'' that the infringement was justified and upheld the law.\n\nOn May 18, 2010 a Jewish public servant won \"a major human rights victory\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ottawacitizen.com/life/Public+servant+claims+rights+victory+following+anti+Semitism+complaint/3075506/story.html|title=Public servant claims rights victory following anti-Semitism complaint|last=Cobb|first=Chris|date=May 27, 2010|work=Ottawa Citizen|access-date=May 27, 2010}}</ref> against the federal government after complaining that her workplace at the Ottawa headquarters of [[Passport Canada]] was poisoned by anti-Semitism. The federal adjudicator ruled<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://decisions.fpslreb-crtespf.gc.ca/fpslreb-crtespf/d/en/item/358553/index.do|title=FPSLREB Decisions: LaBranche v. Treasury Board (Department of Foreign Affairs and International Trade)|last=Pineau|first=Michele A.|date=May 18, 2010|website=Federal Public Sector Labour Relations and Employment Board|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> that some of the public servant's fellow employees discriminated against her because of adherence to Jewish Law ([[Halakha]]) - notably leaving early each Friday to observe the Jewish Sabbath ([[Shabbat]]) and taking Jewish holidays - and that her bosses did little or nothing to help her. The situation escalated from anti-Semitic bullying at her workplace to traumatizing threats when she was accused in an anonymous anti-Semitic message to her superiors to be a [[Mossad]] agent. Another message that followed two weeks later read: \"The Jew sucks your blood. Don't fall into her trap. You will make her go swiftly or we will make her go slowly and painfully.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://decisions.fpslreb-crtespf.gc.ca/fpslreb-crtespf/d/en/item/358553/index.do|title=FPSLREB Decisions: LaBranche v. Treasury Board (Department of Foreign Affairs and International Trade)|last=Pineau|first=Michele A.|date=May 18, 2010|website=Federal Public Sector Labour Relations and Employment Board|page=6 (of the downloadable pdf)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 2, 2019}}</ref>  The public servant launched first an internal grievance against her department in January 2007 alleging breaches of the [[Canadian Human Rights Act]] (CHRA) and the no discrimination clause of the collective agreement with her employer. The grievance was rejected the following October by the federal government. She subsequently took her case to adjudication to the [[Federal Public Sector Labour Relations and Employment Board|Federal Public Service Labour Relations Board]] (FPSLREB) seeking among others damages for pain and suffering, and an admission by the government that her rights were violated. She was supported by the Canadian Association of Professional Employees (CAPE)  which stated on January 18, 2011 on its website that the decision of the FPSLREB \"was a significant win on behalf of the federal government employee.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acep-cape.ca/en/news-events/general-membership-news/news-archive-2008-2012/cape-successful-in-labranche-religious-discrimination-case/|title=CAPE Successful in LaBranche Religious Discrimination Case|last=|first=|date=January 18, 2011|website=Canadian Association of Professional Employees (CAPE)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This case received some attention in national and international media (such as the National Post, LeDroit, McLeans, USA Today, Mekor Rishon, Hamodia).      \n\nOn November 2011 an antisemitic attack took place at the south Winnipeg high school when a teen approached a 15-year-old girl as they crossed paths near his locker and began talking to her. He pulled out a lighter and started flicking it near her head, saying, \"let's burn the Jew\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Turner|first=James|title=Judge agrees lighter attack at a high school not racially motivated|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/breakingnews/Judge-agrees-lighter-attack-at-a-high-school-not-racially-motivated-238505831.html|accessdate=27 April 2014|newspaper=Winnipeg Free Press|date=January 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn April 12, 2012, several Jewish-owned summer homes in [[Val-Morin, Quebec]] were broken into and defaced with swastikas and anti-semitic messages.\n\nAccording to the \"2013 Audit of Antisemitic Incidents\" written by the B'nai Brith Canada, there was a decrease of 5.3% in the number of antisemitic incidents during 2013. Despite that, cases of vandalism rose by 21.8% while violence increased by one incident and harassment cases dropped by 13.9%.<ref>{{cite web|title=2013 Audit of antisemitic incidents |url=http://bnaibrith.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Audit-2013-English.pdf |work=B'nai Brith |accessdate=5 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006081950/http://bnaibrith.ca/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Audit-2013-English.pdf |archivedate=6 October 2014 }}</ref> These incidents include antisemitic graffiti, paintings of swastikas in Jewish neighborhood, firebomb attacks, antisemitic statements, etc.<ref>{{cite web|title=Antisemitic Incidents|url=http://antisemitism.org.il/list/1|work=CFCA|publisher=CFCA|accessdate=26 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211053733/http://antisemitism.org.il/list/1|archive-date=2013-12-11|url-status=dead}}</ref> Antisemitic graffiti and swastika inscriptions has been also found during 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Photo Galleries Racist, anti-Semitic graffiti found near Ottawa River|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/racist-anti-semitic-graffiti-found-near-ottawa-river-1.2615521|accessdate=27 April 2014|newspaper=CBC News|date=Apr 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Swastika was scrawled at the entrance to Kiryas Tosh|url=http://antisemitism.org.il/article/86835/swastika-was-scrawled-entrance-kiryas-tosh|work=CFCA|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, a Toronto police published the 2014 Annual Hate/Bias Crime Statistical Report. According to the report, the victim group most targeted in 2014 was the Jewish community, with occurrence of 30% of all the hate crimes in Toronto. The total number of reported incidents that occurred on antisemitic base was 52, which makes the Jewish community to the most targeted population to assaults.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lungen|first1=Paul|title=Police find Jews most targeted for hate crimes|url=http://www.cjnews.com/news/canada?q=node/137762|accessdate=30 March 2015|work=The Canadian Jewish News|date=March 23, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Police find Jews most targeted for hate crimes|url=http://antisemitism.org.il/article/95184/police-find-jews-most-targeted-hate-crimes|website=CFCA|publisher=Toronto Police|accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, [[B'nai B'rith]] Canada published the \"2014 Audit of Antisemitic Incidents\". Contrasted with 2014 results, there was an increase of almost 30% in antisemitic incidents. The audit showed a peak of acts during July with the onset of operation [[2014 Israel\u2013Gaza conflict|Protective Edge]] in Gaza. According to the report, most of the incidents (1013) were defined as \"harassment\", when the fewest (19) were under the category of \"violence\".  As in previous years audits, [[Ontario]] leads the number of incidents reported at 961, or 59% of the total.<ref name=\"B'nei Brith\">{{cite web|title=2014 Annual Audit Of Antisemitic Incidents|url=https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/bnaibrithcanada/pages/174/attachments/original/1433967668/2014_report_English.pdf?1433967668|publisher=B'nei Brith|accessdate=30 June 2015}}</ref>  (See section on the \"New antisemitism\" in Canada below.) \n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n|+ Annual incidents figures by category 2012\u20132014 <ref name=\"B'nei Brith\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | 2012\n! scope=\"col\" | 2013\n! scope=\"col\" | 2014\n<!-- ! scope=\"col\" | 2015 -->\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1. Vandalism\n| 319 || 388|| 238  \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2. Violence\n| 13 || 14 || 19 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3. Harassment\n| 1013 || 872 || 1370 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Total\n| 1345 ||  1274 || 1627 \n|}\nAccording to a phone survey of 510 Canadians conducted by the [[Anti-Defamation League|ADL]] (Anti-Defamation League) in 2013\u20132014,  an estimated 14% (+/&minus; 4.4%) of the adult population in Canada harbor substantial antisemitic opinions.<ref>{{cite web|title=ADL global 100- Canada|url=http://global100.adl.org/#country/canada/2014|publisher=Anti-Defamation League|accessdate=14 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2016 the Toronto Police published its annual report of hate-crimes during 2015. According to it, the Jewish population is the group most targeted to hate-crimes, especially when it comes to mischief to property occurrences.<ref name=TorontoPolice>{{cite web |url=https://www.torontopolice.on.ca/publications/files/reports/2015hatecrimereport.pdf |publisher=Toronto Police Service |title=2015 Annual Hate/Bias Crime Statistical Report |year=2015}}</ref> Moreover, in occurrences involve religion, most of the victims are part of the Jewish community (in 31 out of 58 cases). The report found that the Jewish community makes up only 3.8% of the religious population in the City of Toronto but was victimized in approximately 23% of the total hate/bias crimes in 2015.<ref name=TorontoPolice />\n\nIn July 2019, a Jewish man wearing a yarmulke was assaulted by a taxi driver in Montreal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jewish man wearing kippah assaulted by taxi driver in Montreal |url=https://www.jta.org/quick-reads/jewish-man-wearing-kippah-assaulted-by-taxi-driver-in-montreal |work=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]}}</ref>\n\n== \"New antisemitism\" in Canada ==\nIn 2009, the [[Canadian Parliamentary Coalition to Combat Antisemitism]] was established by [[List of federal political parties in Canada#Political parties currently represented in the House of Commons|major federal political parties]] to investigate and combat antisemitism - particularly what is referred to as the [[new antisemitism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cpcca.ca/about.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-05-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706173716/http://www.cpcca.ca/about.htm |archivedate=2011-07-06 }}</ref> It is argued that this form of hate targets Israel, consisting of and fed by allegations of Israeli \"war crimes\" and similar claims. Anti-Israel actions that led to the formation of a Parliamentary Coalition included boycott campaigns on university campuses and in some churches, spilling over into attacks on synagogues, Jewish institutions and individuals. Activities such as \"Israel Apartheid Week\" at [[Concordia University|Concordia]] (Montreal), York University and the University of Toronto, and boycott campaigns targeting Israel (BDS) included what some considered as \"forms of antisemitism\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.macleans.ca/education/university/utoronto-and-york-students-launch-bds-campaign/|title=UToronto and York students launch BDS campaign - Macleans.ca|date=2011-03-20|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2016/03/06/york-university-accused-of-allowing-anti-semitism-to-spread|title=York University accused of allowing anti-Semitism to spread|website=Toronto Sun|access-date=2016-09-30}}</ref>\n\nOn September 9, 2002, at Concordia University a pro-[[State of Palestine|Palestinian]] group sought to prevent a [[Anti-Netanyahu riot at Concordia University|scheduled speech]] by the then former (and now current) [[Israel]]i Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]], and the event was cancelled as a result.<ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20030115/concordia030115?s_name=&no_ads= |title=Concordia U. regrets anti-Netanyahu riot |author=Canadian Press |date=January 15, 2003 |publisher=CTV.ca |accessdate=December 25, 2019 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080601103256/http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20030115/concordia030115?s_name=&no_ads= |archivedate=June 1, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nAt York University in 2009, violent pro-Palestinian activists attacked Jewish students, shouting \"Zionism equals racism!\" and \"Racists off campus!\" One witness stated that the attackers started banging the door and windows, intimidating Jewish students and screaming antisemitic slurs such as \"Die Jew\", \"Get the hell off campus\", \"Go back to Israel\", and \"F---ing Jew\".<ref name=\"Shefa\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cjnews.com/node/82752|title=Jewish students under 'siege' at York U|last=Shefa|first=Sheri|date=February 19, 2009|work=[[Canadian Jewish News]]|access-date=March 26, 2015}}</ref> The students barricaded themselves inside the Hillel offices, where protesters reportedly banged on the windows and attempted to force their way in.  Police were called to escort Jewish students through the protesters.<ref>[http://www.jewishtribune.ca/TribuneV2/index.php/200902171360/Democracy-takes-a-beating-at-York.html Democracy takes a beating at York] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706183810/http://www.jewishtribune.ca/TribuneV2/index.php/200902171360/Democracy-takes-a-beating-at-York.html |date=July 6, 2011 }} by Atara Beck, ''The Jewish Tribune'', February 17, 2009.</ref><ref>[http://network.nationalpost.com/np/blogs/fullcomment/archive/2009/02/12/an-eyewitness-account-of-this-week-s-aggressive-intimidation-of-jewish-students-at-york-university.aspx An eyewitness account of this week's aggressive intimidation of Jewish students at York University]{{dead link|date=July 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}} by Jonathan Blake Karoly, ''National Post'', February 12, 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.canada.com/news/story.html?id=1343206 Campuses awash in tension over Israel apartheid week] By Craig Offman, ''National Post'', March 3, 2009 (posted on Canada.com).</ref><ref>[http://network.nationalpost.com/np/blogs/toronto/archive/2009/03/05/york-university-sanctions-four-student-groups-for-feb-11-incident.aspx York University sanctions student groups over rally clashes]{{dead link|date=July 2016|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}, ''National Post'', March 5, 2009</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=12hApMpQlds|title=Krisna Saravanamuttu and Jesse Zimmerman barricade Jewish students at York|last=|first=|date=June 29, 2010|website=Youtube|publisher=|accessdate=March 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 antisemitic graffiti was scrawled on a Jewish memorial in Ottawa, and attributed to a pro-Palestinian group.\n\nLeading Canadian Jewish groups such as [[Centre for Israel and Jewish Affairs|CIJA]] and [[B'nai Brith Canada]] took the lead in responding, while other organisations such as the Canadian branch of the [[New Israel Fund]] chose not to play a role. In August 2012, CIJA opposed the [[United Church of Canada]] (UCC) boycott and divestment campaign, and CIJA's CEO [[Shimon Fogel]] distinguished between criticism of Israeli policies and initiatives that single out Israel for economic coercion.<sup>[[Centre for Israel and Jewish Affairs#cite note-14|[14]]]</sup>\n\n==See also==\n* [[:Category:Jewish museums in Canada|Jewish museums in Canada]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{citation |last =  Davies|first =Alan T. |coauthor= |year = 1992|title =Antisemitism in Canada: history and interpretation\n  |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=3kLgn7dIEwIC&lpg=PP1&dq=Antisemitism%20in%20Canada&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=true|publisher= Wilfrid Laurier University Press|isbn= 0-88920-216-8 |accessdate = }}\n* [[Montreal Holocaust Museum]]. (2018). [https://museeholocauste.ca/app/uploads/2018/10/brief_history_holocaust_reference_tool.pdf A ''Brief History of the Holocaust'']. Montreal, Quebec.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ushmm.org/museum/exhibit/focus/antisemitism/voices/transcript/?content=20080605 ''Voices on Antisemitism'' Interview with Irwin Cotler] from the [http://www.ushmm.org/ United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]\n* [http://faculty.marianopolis.edu/c.belanger/quebechistory/readings/CanadaandJewishRefugeesinthe1930s.html \"Why did Canada Refuse to Admit Jewish Refugees in the 1930's?\"]\n\n{{Antisemitism topics}}\n{{North America in topic|Antisemitism in}}\n\n[[Category:Antisemitism in Canada| ]]\n[[Category:Judaism-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in Canada]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism by country|Canada]]\n", "name_user": "JosephQuesnel", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling mistake corrected", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antisemitism_in_Canada"}
{"title_page": "Election ink", "text_new": "[[File:Iraq-election2005-V.jpg|thumb|Anonymous voter shows stained finger during the Iraqi election of 2005.]]\n  \n{{voting}}\n\n'''Electoral ink''', '''indelible''' '''ink''', '''electoral stain''' or '''phosphoric ink''' is a semi-permanent [[ink]] or [[dye]] that is applied to the [[forefinger]] (usually) of [[voters]] during [[elections]] in order to prevent [[electoral fraud]] such as double voting. It is an effective method for countries where identification documents for citizens are not always standardised or institutionalised. Election ink uses [[silver nitrate]], and excessive exposure can cause [[argyria]]. It was first used during the [[1962 Indian general election]], in [[Mysore State]], now the modern-day state of [[Karnataka]].\n\n==Application==\nElectoral stain is used as an effective security feature to prevent double voting in elections. Ink is normally applied to the left hand index finger, especially to the [[cuticle]] where it is almost impossible to remove quickly. Ink may be applied in a variety of ways, depending on circumstance and preference. The most common methods are via dipping bottles with sponge inserts, bottles with a brush applicators, spray bottles, and [[marker pens]]. With all methods the finger should be left to dry for 15\u201330 seconds and exposed to light before being cleaned to ensure the mark remains visible for the desired length of time.\n\n==Composition==\nElectoral stain typically contains a pigment for instant recognition, a [[silver nitrate]] which stains the skin on exposure to ultraviolet light, leaving a mark that is impossible to wash off and is only removed as external skin cells are replaced. Industry standard electoral inks contain 10%, 14% or 18% silver nitrate solution, depending on the length of time the mark is required to be visible. Although normally water-based, electoral stains occasionally contain a solvent such as alcohol to allow for faster drying, especially when used with dipping bottles, which may also contain a biocide to ensure bacteria are not transferred from voter to voter. Silver chloride can be easily removed by hydroxides, hence other photosensitive pigmentation needs to be added.\n\n==Longevity==\nElection stain typically stays on [[Human skin|skin]] for 72\u201396 hours, lasting 2 to 4 weeks on the [[fingernail]] and [[cuticle]] area. The election ink used puts a permanent mark on the cuticle area which disappears only with the growth of new nail. It can take up to 4 months for the stain to be replaced completely by new nail growth. Stain with concentrations of [[silver nitrate]] higher than 18% have been found to have no effect on stain longevity, as even with stronger solutions [[silver nitrate]] doesn't have a [[photosensitive reaction]] on live skin cells. This means that the stain will wear off as new skin grows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ptcl.chem.ox.ac.uk/~hmc/hsci/chemicals/silver_nitrate.html |title='&#39;Chemical Safety Database'&#39; |publisher=Ptcl.chem.ox.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-04-30}}</ref> Silver nitrate is an irritant and frequently harmful at 25% solution and above, even being used as an effective, if painful, cauterizing agent in the treatment of [[rhinitis]] at that concentration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pakmedinet.com/10886 |title='&#39;PakMediNet'&#39; |publisher=Pakmedinet.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-30}}</ref> At 25% the silver nitrate content will also start to precipitate depending on conditions, forming fine crystals which can also be irritating on skin and reducing the active dissolved [[silver nitrate]] back to as low as 18%.\n\n==Colour==\nElectoral stain is traditionally violet in colour, before the photosensitive element takes effect to leave a black or brown mark. However, for the [[2005 Surinamese legislative election]], orange replaced violet as the colour for marking the voters' fingers as it was found to last just as long and be more appealing to voters, as it resembled the [[national colours]].\n\n==Efficiency==\nMarker pens are the most efficient use of ink, with one 5\u00a0ml pen able to mark 600 people, although dipping bottles are often preferred, despite a 100 ml bottle only marking 1000. This may be due to the iconic images associated with the Iraqi and Afghan elections of the early 21st century. Dipping bottles can leave a more comprehensive stain of slightly longer longevity (depending on silver nitrate content) than markers can. However marker pens are much cheaper and easier to transport, reducing costs to the election organisers considerably, and the advised option when stains are only needed to be guaranteed for 3 to 5 days. Marker pens also leave a much smaller mark when properly applied, which is more agreeable to many voters.\n\n==Controversies==\nIn the [[2004 Afghan presidential election]], allegations of electoral fraud arose around the use of indelible ink stains, which many claimed were easily washed off.<ref>{{cite web|author=Scott Baldauf |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2004/1012/p06s01-wosc.html |title='&#39;An Afghan 'Hanging chad' Dispute'&#39; |publisher=Csmonitor.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-30}}</ref> Election officials had chosen to use the more efficient marker pen option; however, regular marker pens were also sent out to polling stations, which led to confusion and some people being marked with less permanent ink.<ref>{{cite web|last=Raman |first=Sunil |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/3736590.stm |title='&#39;India link to Afghan ink stink'&#39; |publisher=BBC News |date=2004-10-12 |accessdate=2014-04-30}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2008 Malaysian general election]], the election authorities canceled the use of Electoral Stain a week before voters went to the polls,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.my.msn.com/regional/article.aspx?cp-documentid=1274414 |title='&#39;MSN News article'&#39; |publisher=News.my.msn.com |accessdate=2014-04-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513080647/http://news.my.msn.com/regional/article.aspx?cp-documentid=1274414 |archivedate=2008-05-13 }}</ref> saying it would be unconstitutional to prevent people from voting even if they had already had their fingers stained. Additionally they cited reports of ink being smuggled in from neighboring [[Thailand]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Wong |first=Raphael |url=http://thestar.com.my/election/story.asp?file=/2008/3/5/election2008/20540844&sec=Election2008&focus=1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430202643/http://www.thestar.com.my/election/story.asp?file=%2F2008%2F3%2F5%2Felection2008%2F20540844&sec=Election2008&focus=1 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-04-30 |title='&#39;Ink Washout - The Star'&#39; |publisher=Thestar.com.my |date=2008-03-05 |accessdate=2014-04-30 }}</ref> in order to mark peoples' fingers before they had a chance to vote, thus denying them their rights.\n\nDuring the [[2008 Zimbabwean presidential election]], reports surfaced that those who had chosen not to vote were attacked and beaten by government sponsored mobs. The mobs attacked those without ink on their finger.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/7478399.stm |title=World &#124; Africa &#124; Tsvangirai rejects 'sham' ballot |publisher=BBC News |date=2008-06-27 |accessdate=2014-04-30}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2010 Afghan elections the Taliban delivered night letters threatening to cut off anybody's finger who was marked with indelible ink.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-16/taliban-plans-attacks-to-disrupt-afghan-vote-intended-to-promote-stability.html|title=New Candidates May Win Half of Afghan Parliament Seats Amid Ballot Fraud|author=Eltaf Najafizada and James Rupert|date=20 October 2010|work=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2013 Malaysian general election]], in light of the first ever implementation of Electoral Stain, voters reported that the ink could be easily washed off with running water, despite assurances by the [[Election Commission of Malaysia]] on the contrary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia-pacific/2013/05/20135112390608902.html |title=Election ink under scrutiny in Malaysia - Asia-Pacific |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date= |accessdate=2014-04-30}}</ref>\n\n==International use==<!-- PLEASE RESPECT ALPHABETICAL ORDER -->\nSome of the countries that have used election ink at some point include:\n{{colbegin|colwidth=15em}}\n*[[Afghanistan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/aug/20/afghanistan-election-ink|title=Afghanistan election ink safeguard fails detergent test|first=Jon|last=Boone|date=20 August 2009|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n*[[Albania]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaneu.com/skopje-interested-indedible-ink-albania-elections/|title=Skopje interested on the indedible ink used by Albania in the elections|website=www.balkaneu.com}}</ref>\n*[[The Bahamas]]<ref name=ifes1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ifes.org/sites/default/files/ifes_gerhard_atic_letic_erben_white_paper_indelible_ink_in_elections_may_2019.pdf|title=Indelible Ink in Elections|year=2019|author=Anne-Sofie Holm Gerhard, Melika Atic, Panto Letic and Peter Erben|website=[[International Foundation for Electoral Systems]]|pages=20-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108205514/https://www.ifes.org/sites/default/files/ifes_gerhard_atic_letic_erben_white_paper_indelible_ink_in_elections_may_2019.pdf|archive-date=2019-11-08}}</ref>\n*[[Algeria]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gettyimages.no/detail/news-photo/an-algerian-man-with-ink-applied-on-his-forefinger-prepares-news-photo/484355839|title=An Algerian man, with ink applied on his forefinger, prepares to vote a polling station in the Chanot Park on April 12, 2014 in Marseille, southern France|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Dominica]]<ref>{{cite\nweb|url=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dominica|</ref>\n*[[Egypt]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/worldnews/9287835/Egypt-elections-in-pictures.html?frame=2229191|title=Egypt elections in pictures|date=24 May 2012|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n*[[Guatemala]]<ref name=ifes1></ref>\n*[[India]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/apr/17/indian-elections-ink-mark-voters-symbol-democratic-privilege|title=Indian elections: voters united by anti-fraud ink mark|first=Anu|last=Anand|date=17 April 2014|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n*[[Indonesia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indonesiaatmelbourne.unimelb.edu.au/key-facts-the-indonesian-legislative-election/|title=Key facts: the Indonesian Legislative Election|date=8 April 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Iraq]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/world/as-iraq-moves-on-with-vote-falluja-trapped-by-sins-of-the-past-5174869/|title=As Iraq moves on with vote, Falluja trapped by sins of the past|date=2018-05-13|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-05-17|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*[[Pakistan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/616058/election-fraud-the-curious-case-of-magnetic-ink/|title=Election fraud: The curious case of magnetic ink  - The Express Tribune|date=10 October 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Lebanon]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lebanon-politics-idUSKCN0YL1VI|title=Sunni hawk wins Lebanon vote, risking new tensions|first=Tom|last=Perry|publisher=}}</ref>\n*Libya\n*[[Malaysia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miricitysharing.com/remove-election-ink-from-finger-after-voting/|title=Remove Election Ink From Finger After Voting|website=www.miricitysharing.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/s/1583687/ahead-of-ge14-ec-orders-100000-bottles-of-indelible-ink-from-india|title=Ahead of GE14, EC orders 100,000 bottles of indelible ink from India - Malay Mail|website=www.malaymail.com}}</ref>\n*[[Maldives]]<ref name=ifes1></ref>\n*[[Myanmar]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mm.undp.org/content/myanmar/en/home/presscenter/pressreleases/2015/11/25/undp-provided-indelible-ink-in-myanmar-elections-a-powerful-integrity-tool-.html|title=UNDP Provided Indelible Ink in Myanmar Elections: A Powerful Integrity Tool|website=UNDP in Myanmar}}</ref>\n*[[Nepal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://electionstandards.cartercenter.org/observing-nepals-2013-constituent-assembly-election/|title=Observing Nepal's 2013 Constituent Assembly Election - Election Standards at The Carter Center|website=electionstandards.cartercenter.org}}</ref>\n*[[Nicaragua]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/nicaragua-election-observers-report-problems-1.1076155|title=Nicaragua election observers report problems - CBC News|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Peru]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archive.peruthisweek.com/news-14726-politics-congress-eliminates-use-ink-peruvian-elections |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-06-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816071944/http://archive.peruthisweek.com/news-14726-politics-congress-eliminates-use-ink-peruvian-elections |archive-date=2016-08-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Philippines]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-36244456|title=Hardliner claims Philippine election win|date=9 May 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n*[[Saint Kitts and Nevis]]<ref>http://www.oas.org/sap/docs/DECO/2010/SAINT_KITTS_NEVIS_JAN_25_2010.pdf</ref>\n*[[South Africa]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gettyimages.co.uk/pictures/south-african-woman-gets-ink-on-her-finger-after-she-voted-news-photo-86148930|title=A South African woman gets ink on her fi|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Sri Lanka]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gettyimages.no/detail/news-photo/sri-lankan-election-official-marks-a-voters-finger-with-news-photo/3193980|title=Sri Lankan Voters Go To The Polls|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Sudan]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://radiotamazuj.org/en/article/sudan-voting-extended-ink-washing-voters-fingers |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-05-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602205553/https://radiotamazuj.org/en/article/sudan-voting-extended-ink-washing-voters-fingers |archive-date=2016-06-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Syria]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/syria-holds-parliamentary-polls-in-regime-held-areas/|title=Syria holds parliamentary polls in regime-held areas|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Tunisia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-30569318|title=Tunisia veteran claims election win|date=22 December 2014|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n*[[Turkey]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailysabah.com/feature/2015/10/30/the-brief-history-of-elections-in-turkey|title=The brief history of elections in Turkey|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Venezuela]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-35019111|title=Venezuela's Socialists trounced in vote|date=7 December 2015|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> (until 2017)<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=CNE anunci\u00f3 que no usar\u00e1 tinta indeleble para la elecci\u00f3n de la ANC|url=http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/politica/cne-anuncio-que-usara-tinta-indeleble-para-eleccion-anc_192284|date=10 July 2017|accessdate=27 May 2018|work=El Nacional|location=|page=|number=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180527201724/http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/politica/cne-anuncio-que-usara-tinta-indeleble-para-eleccion-anc_192284|archive-date=27 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110713003518/http://www.ifesbuyersguide.com/search.php?keyword=ink IFES Buyers Guide]\n\n[[Category:Inks]]\n[[Category:Electoral fraud]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Iraq-election2005-V.jpg|thumb|Anonymous voter shows stained finger during the Iraqi election of 2005.]]\n  \n{{voting}}\n\n'''Electoral ink''', '''indelible''' '''ink''', '''electoral stain''' or '''phosphoric ink''' is a semi-permanent [[ink]] or [[dye]] that is applied to the [[forefinger]] (usually) of [[voters]] during [[elections]] in order to prevent [[electoral fraud]] such as double voting. It is an effective method for countries where identification documents for citizens are not always standardised or institutionalised. Election ink uses [[silver nitrate]], and excessive exposure can cause [[argyria]]. It was first used during the [[1962 Indian general election]], in [[Mysore State]], now the modern-day state of [[Karnataka]].\n\n==Application==\nElectoral stain is used as an effective security feature to prevent double voting in elections. Ink is normally applied to the left hand index finger, especially to the [[cuticle]] where it is almost impossible to remove quickly. Ink may be applied in a variety of ways, depending on circumstance and preference. The most common methods are via dipping bottles with sponge inserts, bottles with a brush applicators, spray bottles, and [[marker pens]]. With all methods the finger should be left to dry for 15\u201330 seconds and exposed to light before being cleaned to ensure the mark remains visible for the desired length of time.\n\n==Composition==\nElectoral stain typically contains a pigment for instant recognition, a [[silver nitrate]] which stains the skin on exposure to ultraviolet light, leaving a mark that is impossible to wash off and is only removed as external skin cells are replaced. Industry standard electoral inks contain 10%, 14% or 18% silver nitrate solution, depending on the length of time the mark is required to be visible. Although normally water-based, electoral stains occasionally contain a solvent such as alcohol to allow for faster drying, especially when used with dipping bottles, which may also contain a biocide to ensure bacteria are not transferred from voter to voter. Silver chloride can be easily removed by hydroxides, hence other photosensitive pigmentation needs to be added.\n\n==Longevity==\nElection stain typically stays on [[Human skin|skin]] for 72\u201396 hours, lasting 2 to 4 weeks on the [[fingernail]] and [[cuticle]] area. The election ink used puts a permanent mark on the cuticle area which disappears only with the growth of new nail. It can take up to 4 months for the stain to be replaced completely by new nail growth. Stain with concentrations of [[silver nitrate]] higher than 18% have been found to have no effect on stain longevity, as even with stronger solutions [[silver nitrate]] doesn't have a [[photosensitive reaction]] on live skin cells. This means that the stain will wear off as new skin grows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ptcl.chem.ox.ac.uk/~hmc/hsci/chemicals/silver_nitrate.html |title='&#39;Chemical Safety Database'&#39; |publisher=Ptcl.chem.ox.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-04-30}}</ref> Silver nitrate is an irritant and frequently harmful at 25% solution and above, even being used as an effective, if painful, cauterizing agent in the treatment of [[rhinitis]] at that concentration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pakmedinet.com/10886 |title='&#39;PakMediNet'&#39; |publisher=Pakmedinet.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-30}}</ref> At 25% the silver nitrate content will also start to precipitate depending on conditions, forming fine crystals which can also be irritating on skin and reducing the active dissolved [[silver nitrate]] back to as low as 18%.\n\n==Colour==\nElectoral stain is traditionally violet in colour, before the photosensitive element takes effect to leave a black or brown mark. However, for the [[2005 Surinamese legislative election]], orange replaced violet as the colour for marking the voters' fingers as it was found to last just as long and be more appealing to voters, as it resembled the [[national colours]].\n\n==Efficiency==\nMarker pens are the most efficient use of ink, with one 5ml pen able to mark 600 people, although dipping bottles are often preferred, despite a 100 ml bottle only marking 1000. This may be due to the iconic images associated with the Iraqi and Afghan elections of the early 21st century. Dipping bottles can leave a more comprehensive stain of slightly longer longevity (depending on silver nitrate content) than markers can. However marker pens are much cheaper and easier to transport, reducing costs to the election organisers considerably, and the advised option when stains are only needed to be guaranteed for 3 to 5 days. Marker pens also leave a much smaller mark when properly applied, which is more agreeable to many voters.\n\n==Controversies==\nIn the [[2004 Afghan presidential election]], allegations of electoral fraud arose around the use of indelible ink stains, which many claimed were easily washed off.<ref>{{cite web|author=Scott Baldauf |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2004/1012/p06s01-wosc.html |title='&#39;An Afghan 'Hanging chad' Dispute'&#39; |publisher=Csmonitor.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-30}}</ref> Election officials had chosen to use the more efficient marker pen option; however, regular marker pens were also sent out to polling stations, which led to confusion and some people being marked with less permanent ink.<ref>{{cite web|last=Raman |first=Sunil |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/3736590.stm |title='&#39;India link to Afghan ink stink'&#39; |publisher=BBC News |date=2004-10-12 |accessdate=2014-04-30}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2008 Malaysian general election]], the election authorities canceled the use of Electoral Stain a week before voters went to the polls,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.my.msn.com/regional/article.aspx?cp-documentid=1274414 |title='&#39;MSN News article'&#39; |publisher=News.my.msn.com |accessdate=2014-04-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513080647/http://news.my.msn.com/regional/article.aspx?cp-documentid=1274414 |archivedate=2008-05-13 }}</ref> saying it would be unconstitutional to prevent people from voting even if they had already had their fingers stained. Additionally they cited reports of ink being smuggled in from neighboring [[Thailand]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Wong |first=Raphael |url=http://thestar.com.my/election/story.asp?file=/2008/3/5/election2008/20540844&sec=Election2008&focus=1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430202643/http://www.thestar.com.my/election/story.asp?file=%2F2008%2F3%2F5%2Felection2008%2F20540844&sec=Election2008&focus=1 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-04-30 |title='&#39;Ink Washout - The Star'&#39; |publisher=Thestar.com.my |date=2008-03-05 |accessdate=2014-04-30 }}</ref> in order to mark peoples' fingers before they had a chance to vote, thus denying them their rights.\n\nDuring the [[2008 Zimbabwean presidential election]], reports surfaced that those who had chosen not to vote were attacked and beaten by government sponsored mobs. The mobs attacked those without ink on their finger.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/7478399.stm |title=World &#124; Africa &#124; Tsvangirai rejects 'sham' ballot |publisher=BBC News |date=2008-06-27 |accessdate=2014-04-30}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2010 Afghan elections the Taliban delivered night letters threatening to cut off anybody's finger who was marked with indelible ink.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-16/taliban-plans-attacks-to-disrupt-afghan-vote-intended-to-promote-stability.html|title=New Candidates May Win Half of Afghan Parliament Seats Amid Ballot Fraud|author=Eltaf Najafizada and James Rupert|date=20 October 2010|work=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2013 Malaysian general election]], in light of the first ever implementation of Electoral Stain, voters reported that the ink could be easily washed off with running water, despite assurances by the [[Election Commission of Malaysia]] on the contrary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia-pacific/2013/05/20135112390608902.html |title=Election ink under scrutiny in Malaysia - Asia-Pacific |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date= |accessdate=2014-04-30}}</ref>\n\n==International use==<!-- PLEASE RESPECT ALPHABETICAL ORDER -->\nSome of the countries that have used election ink at some point include:\n{{colbegin|colwidth=15em}}\n*[[Afghanistan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/aug/20/afghanistan-election-ink|title=Afghanistan election ink safeguard fails detergent test|first=Jon|last=Boone|date=20 August 2009|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n*[[Albania]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaneu.com/skopje-interested-indedible-ink-albania-elections/|title=Skopje interested on the indedible ink used by Albania in the elections|website=www.balkaneu.com}}</ref>\n*[[The Bahamas]]<ref name=ifes1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ifes.org/sites/default/files/ifes_gerhard_atic_letic_erben_white_paper_indelible_ink_in_elections_may_2019.pdf|title=Indelible Ink in Elections|year=2019|author=Anne-Sofie Holm Gerhard, Melika Atic, Panto Letic and Peter Erben|website=[[International Foundation for Electoral Systems]]|pages=20-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108205514/https://www.ifes.org/sites/default/files/ifes_gerhard_atic_letic_erben_white_paper_indelible_ink_in_elections_may_2019.pdf|archive-date=2019-11-08}}</ref>\n*[[Algeria]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gettyimages.no/detail/news-photo/an-algerian-man-with-ink-applied-on-his-forefinger-prepares-news-photo/484355839|title=An Algerian man, with ink applied on his forefinger, prepares to vote a polling station in the Chanot Park on April 12, 2014 in Marseille, southern France|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Dominica]]<ref>{{cite\nweb|url=https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dominica|</ref>\n*[[Egypt]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/worldnews/9287835/Egypt-elections-in-pictures.html?frame=2229191|title=Egypt elections in pictures|date=24 May 2012|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n*[[Guatemala]]<ref name=ifes1></ref>\n*[[India]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/apr/17/indian-elections-ink-mark-voters-symbol-democratic-privilege|title=Indian elections: voters united by anti-fraud ink mark|first=Anu|last=Anand|date=17 April 2014|website=the Guardian}}</ref>\n*[[Indonesia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indonesiaatmelbourne.unimelb.edu.au/key-facts-the-indonesian-legislative-election/|title=Key facts: the Indonesian Legislative Election|date=8 April 2014|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Iraq]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/world/as-iraq-moves-on-with-vote-falluja-trapped-by-sins-of-the-past-5174869/|title=As Iraq moves on with vote, Falluja trapped by sins of the past|date=2018-05-13|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-05-17|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*[[Pakistan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/616058/election-fraud-the-curious-case-of-magnetic-ink/|title=Election fraud: The curious case of magnetic ink  - The Express Tribune|date=10 October 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Lebanon]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-lebanon-politics-idUSKCN0YL1VI|title=Sunni hawk wins Lebanon vote, risking new tensions|first=Tom|last=Perry|publisher=}}</ref>\n*Libya\n*[[Malaysia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miricitysharing.com/remove-election-ink-from-finger-after-voting/|title=Remove Election Ink From Finger After Voting|website=www.miricitysharing.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.malaymail.com/s/1583687/ahead-of-ge14-ec-orders-100000-bottles-of-indelible-ink-from-india|title=Ahead of GE14, EC orders 100,000 bottles of indelible ink from India - Malay Mail|website=www.malaymail.com}}</ref>\n*[[Maldives]]<ref name=ifes1></ref>\n*[[Myanmar]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mm.undp.org/content/myanmar/en/home/presscenter/pressreleases/2015/11/25/undp-provided-indelible-ink-in-myanmar-elections-a-powerful-integrity-tool-.html|title=UNDP Provided Indelible Ink in Myanmar Elections: A Powerful Integrity Tool|website=UNDP in Myanmar}}</ref>\n*[[Nepal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://electionstandards.cartercenter.org/observing-nepals-2013-constituent-assembly-election/|title=Observing Nepal's 2013 Constituent Assembly Election - Election Standards at The Carter Center|website=electionstandards.cartercenter.org}}</ref>\n*[[Nicaragua]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/nicaragua-election-observers-report-problems-1.1076155|title=Nicaragua election observers report problems - CBC News|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Peru]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archive.peruthisweek.com/news-14726-politics-congress-eliminates-use-ink-peruvian-elections |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-06-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816071944/http://archive.peruthisweek.com/news-14726-politics-congress-eliminates-use-ink-peruvian-elections |archive-date=2016-08-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Philippines]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-36244456|title=Hardliner claims Philippine election win|date=9 May 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n*[[Saint Kitts and Nevis]]<ref>http://www.oas.org/sap/docs/DECO/2010/SAINT_KITTS_NEVIS_JAN_25_2010.pdf</ref>\n*[[South Africa]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gettyimages.co.uk/pictures/south-african-woman-gets-ink-on-her-finger-after-she-voted-news-photo-86148930|title=A South African woman gets ink on her fi|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Sri Lanka]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gettyimages.no/detail/news-photo/sri-lankan-election-official-marks-a-voters-finger-with-news-photo/3193980|title=Sri Lankan Voters Go To The Polls|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Sudan]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://radiotamazuj.org/en/article/sudan-voting-extended-ink-washing-voters-fingers |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-05-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602205553/https://radiotamazuj.org/en/article/sudan-voting-extended-ink-washing-voters-fingers |archive-date=2016-06-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[Syria]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/syria-holds-parliamentary-polls-in-regime-held-areas/|title=Syria holds parliamentary polls in regime-held areas|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Tunisia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-30569318|title=Tunisia veteran claims election win|date=22 December 2014|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n*[[Turkey]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailysabah.com/feature/2015/10/30/the-brief-history-of-elections-in-turkey|title=The brief history of elections in Turkey|publisher=}}</ref>\n*[[Venezuela]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-35019111|title=Venezuela's Socialists trounced in vote|date=7 December 2015|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> (until 2017)<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=CNE anunci\u00f3 que no usar\u00e1 tinta indeleble para la elecci\u00f3n de la ANC|url=http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/politica/cne-anuncio-que-usara-tinta-indeleble-para-eleccion-anc_192284|date=10 July 2017|accessdate=27 May 2018|work=El Nacional|location=|page=|number=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180527201724/http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/politica/cne-anuncio-que-usara-tinta-indeleble-para-eleccion-anc_192284|archive-date=27 May 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110713003518/http://www.ifesbuyersguide.com/search.php?keyword=ink IFES Buyers Guide]\n\n[[Category:Inks]]\n[[Category:Electoral fraud]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEfficiency:fmt", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Election_ink"}
